{"title_page": "Batubara Regency", "text_new": "{{expand Indonesian|topic=|otherarticle=Kabupaten Batu Bara|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name   = Batubara Regency <br/> \u0628\u0627\u062a\u0648\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\n| image_skyline   = \n| imagesize       = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| settlement_type = [[List of regencies and cities of Indonesia|Regency]]\n| image_seal      = Lambang Kabupaten Batubara.png\n| motto           = \n| image_map       = Lokasi Sumatra Utara Kabupaten Batu Bara.svg\n| map_alt         =\n| map_caption     = \n| subdivision_type  = Country\n| subdivision_name  = [[Indonesia]]\n| subdivision_type1 = Province\n| subdivision_name1 = North Sumatra\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Regency seat]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Limapuluh]]\n| leader_title      = Regent\n| leader_name       = Zahir\n| leader_title1     = Vice Regent\n| leader_name1      = Oky Iqbal Frima\n| leader_title2     = Chairman of Council of Representatives\n| leader_name2      = Syafi'i ([[PDI-P]])\n| leader_title3     = Vice Chairmen of Council of Representatives\n| leader_name3      = Ismar Komri ([[Golkar]]) and Safrizal ([[Gerindra]])\n| area_magnitude    = \n| area_total_km2    = 922.2\n| elevation_m       = \n| population_as_of  = mid 2018\n| population_total  = 412992\n| population_density_km2   = auto\n| population_footnotes     = <ref>Badan Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2019.</ref>\n| timezone1         = [[Time in Indonesia|WIB]]\n| utc_offset1       = +7\n| timezone1_DST     = \n| utc_offset1_DST   = \n| footnotes         = \n| website           = {{URL|http://www.batubarakab.go.id/}}\n}}\n'''Batubara Regency''' is a [[Regencies of Indonesia|regency]] on [[North Sumatra]]'s eastern shoreline, with [[Limapuluh]] as its seat. It was carved out from the seven most westerly coastal districts of [[Asahan Regency]] with effect from 15 June 2007. The new regency covers an area of 922.2 km<sup>2</sup>, and had a population of 375,885 at the 2010 Census and 400,406 at the 2015 Intermediate Census; the latest official estimate (for mid 2018) is 412,992.<ref>Badan Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\nThe regency is divided administratively into seven [[Districts of Indonesia|districts]] (''kecamatan''), tabulated below from east to west with their areas and 2010 Census populations:<ref name=\"Biro Pusat Statistik 2011\">Biro Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2011.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name  || Area in<br> km<sup>2</sup> || Population<br>Census 2010<ref name=\"Biro Pusat Statistik 2011\"/>\n|-\n| Tanjung Tiram ||align=\"right\"|161.4||align=\"right\"|62,964\n|-\n| Sei Balai ||align=\"right\"|71.3||align=\"right\"|26,857\n|-\n| Talawi ||align=\"right\"|110.6||align=\"right\"|53,585\n|-\n| Limpuluh ||align=\"right\"|238.8||align=\"right\"|85,164\n|-\n| Air Putih ||align=\"right\"|38.0||align=\"right\"|46,749\n|-\n| Sei Suka ||align=\"right\"|154.3||align=\"right\"|52,599\n|-\n| Medang Deras ||align=\"right\"|89.5||align=\"right\"|47,967\n|}\n\n==Transport==\nOn January 27, 2015 groundbreaking of [[Kuala Tanjung Port]] has been done. The port can accommodate 60 million TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units) per year as the biggest port in West Indonesia, bigger than [[Port of Jakarta|Tanjung Priok Port]], in [[Jakarta]] with only 15 million TEUs per year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medan.tribunnews.com/2015/01/27/presiden-pelabuhan-kuala-tanjung-bakal-besar-sekali |title=\nPresiden: Pelabuhan Kuala Tanjung Bakal Besar Sekali |date=January 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{North Sumatra}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|3|N|99.1667|E|source:kolossus-eswiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Regencies of North Sumatra]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Indonesia]]\n\n{{NSumatra-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{expand Indonesian|topic=|otherarticle=Kabupaten Batu Bara|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name   = Batubara Regency <br/> \u0628\u0627\u062a\u0648\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0627\n| image_skyline   = \n| imagesize       = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| settlement_type = [[List of regencies and cities of Indonesia|Regency]]\n| image_seal      = Lambang Kabupaten Batubara.png\n| motto           = \n| image_map       = Lokasi Sumatra Utara Kabupaten Batu Bara.svg\n| map_alt         =\n| map_caption     = \n| subdivision_type  = Country\n| subdivision_name  = [[Indonesia]]\n| subdivision_type1 = Province\n| subdivision_name1 = North Sumatra\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Regency seat]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Limapuluh]]\n| leader_title      = Regent\n| leader_name       = Zahir\n| leader_title1     = Vice Regent\n| leader_name1      = Oky Iqbal Frima\n| leader_title2     = Chairman of Council of Representatives\n| leader_name2      = Syafi'i ([[PDI-P]])\n| leader_title2     = Vice Chairmen of Council of Representatives\n| leader_name2      = Ismar Komri ([[Golkar]]) and Safrizal ([[Gerindra]])\n| area_magnitude    = \n| area_total_km2    = 922.2\n| elevation_m       = \n| population_as_of  = mid 2018\n| population_total  = 412992\n| population_density_km2   = auto\n| population_footnotes     = <ref>Badan Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2019.</ref>\n| timezone1         = [[Time in Indonesia|WIB]]\n| utc_offset1       = +7\n| timezone1_DST     = \n| utc_offset1_DST   = \n| footnotes         = \n| website           = {{URL|http://www.batubarakab.go.id/}}\n}}\n'''Batubara Regency''' is a [[Regencies of Indonesia|regency]] on [[North Sumatra]]'s eastern shoreline, with [[Limapuluh]] as its seat. It was carved out from the seven most westerly coastal districts of [[Asahan Regency]] with effect from 15 June 2007. The new regency covers an area of 922.2 km<sup>2</sup>, and had a population of 375,885 at the 2010 Census and 400,406 at the 2015 Intermediate Census; the latest official estimate (for mid 2018) is 412,992.<ref>Badan Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Administration ==\nThe regency is divided administratively into seven [[Districts of Indonesia|districts]] (''kecamatan''), tabulated below from east to west with their areas and 2010 Census populations:<ref name=\"Biro Pusat Statistik 2011\">Biro Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2011.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name  || Area in<br> km<sup>2</sup> || Population<br>Census 2010<ref name=\"Biro Pusat Statistik 2011\"/>\n|-\n| Tanjung Tiram ||align=\"right\"|161.4||align=\"right\"|62,964\n|-\n| Sei Balai ||align=\"right\"|71.3||align=\"right\"|26,857\n|-\n| Talawi ||align=\"right\"|110.6||align=\"right\"|53,585\n|-\n| Limpuluh ||align=\"right\"|238.8||align=\"right\"|85,164\n|-\n| Air Putih ||align=\"right\"|38.0||align=\"right\"|46,749\n|-\n| Sei Suka ||align=\"right\"|154.3||align=\"right\"|52,599\n|-\n| Medang Deras ||align=\"right\"|89.5||align=\"right\"|47,967\n|}\n\n==Transport==\nOn January 27, 2015 groundbreaking of [[Kuala Tanjung Port]] has been done. The port can accommodate 60 million TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units) per year as the biggest port in West Indonesia, bigger than [[Port of Jakarta|Tanjung Priok Port]], in [[Jakarta]] with only 15 million TEUs per year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medan.tribunnews.com/2015/01/27/presiden-pelabuhan-kuala-tanjung-bakal-besar-sekali |title=\nPresiden: Pelabuhan Kuala Tanjung Bakal Besar Sekali |date=January 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{North Sumatra}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|3|N|99.1667|E|source:kolossus-eswiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Regencies of North Sumatra]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Indonesia]]\n\n{{NSumatra-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Konradtempelhoff", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batubara_Regency"}
{"title_page": "Jewish cemeteries in the London area", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThere are many '''Jewish cemeteries in London'''; some are included in the [[List of cemeteries in London]]. This list includes those cemeteries and also some  on the outskirts of London.  The \"[[Magnificent Seven cemeteries|Magnificent Seven]] private cemeteries\" (dating between 1832 and 1841) were opened primarily to relieve Central London's Anglican churchyards, many with later plots for other faiths such as at [[Highgate Cemetery]] where a number of international Jews of similar fame to some of those in the cemeteries below are buried. [[Brookwood Cemetery]], [[Surrey]], opened in 1852, designated approximately half of the original cemetery to non-Anglicans.\n\n==United Synagogue cemeteries==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! Name  !! Opened !! Borough  !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Alderney Road Jewish Cemetery \n| 1697\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]] \n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| 1852\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Also known as The Great Synagogue Burial Ground, this is Britain's oldest Ashkenazi cemetery.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/alderney-road-cemetery |title=Alderney Road Cemetery |website=[[United Synagogue]] |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/alderney-road-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Bancroft Road Jewish Cemetery \n| 1810\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]] \n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| 1907\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The Maiden Lane Synagogue constructed this cemetery on land formerly known as Globe Fields.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/bancroft-road-cemetery |title=Bancroft Road Cemetery |website=[[United Synagogue]] |access-date=5 April 2020}}<