w.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=BRE017 |title= Liberal Jewish Cemetery |website=[[London Gardens Online]] |publisher=[[London Parks & Gardens Trust]]|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> Several notable British Jews, including members of the [[Sassoon family]], are buried at the cemetery, which also has a Grade II listed war memorial. It is adjacent to [[ Willesden United Synagogue Cemetery]].\n| [http://ljs.org/cemetery/ Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Mile End Nuevo (New) Jewish Cemetery\n| 1733\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| 1922\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Also known as Beth Chaim Jewish Cemetery, it is now within the campus of [[Queen Mary University of London|Queen Mary University]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lookup.london/novo-cemetery/ |title=Novo Cemetery: East London's secret burial groiund |date=13 April 2018 |website=Look up London |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [http://www.iajgsjewishcemeteryproject.org/london/mile-end-cemeteries.html Yes]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Mile End Velho (Old) Jewish Cemetery\n| 1756\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| Yes\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Reputed to be the oldest surviving Jewish cemetery in the United Kingdom (closed before 1800)\n| [http://www.iajgsjewishcemeteryproject.org/london/mile-end-cemeteries.html Yes]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The  Western Cemetery (Cheshunt)\n| 1968\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |  [[Borough of Broxbourne]], [[Hertfordshire]] \n|[[EN postcode area|EN7]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The cemetery, which is managed under Orthodox Jewish guidelines, is run by the Western Foundation.<ref name=\"JJBS\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.jjbs.org.uk/cemeteries/ |title=Cemeteries & Crematoria |website=Jewish Joint Burial Soicety |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [https://www.jjbs.org.uk/cemeteries/ Official website]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" | The  Woodland Cemetery (Cheshunt)\n| 2013\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |  [[Borough of Broxbourne]], [[Hertfordshire]] \n| [[EN postcode area|EN7]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <!-- Remarks -->\n| [https://www.jjbs.org.uk/cemeteries/ Official website]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Former cemeteries==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! Name!! Opened !! Borough  !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Hoxton Jewish Cemetery\n| 1707\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Hackney]]\n| [[N postcode area|N1]]\n| Unknown\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The cemetery was destroyed in 1960, and the remains were transferred to West Ham Jewish Cemetery.\n| [http://cemeteryscribes.com/blog/?p=584 Yes]\n|-\n|}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iajgsjewishcemeteryproject.org/london/index.html Jewish cemeteries in London on the IAJGS website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jewish Cemeteries In London}}\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom| London]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judaism in London]]\n\n\n{{Jewish-cemetery-stub}}\n{{london-struct-stub}}\n{{UK-cemetery-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThere are many '''Jewish cemeteries in London'''; some are included in the [[List of cemeteries in London]]. This list includes those cemeteries and also some  on the outskirts of London.  The \"[[Magnificent Seven cemeteries|Magnificent Seven]] private cemeteries\" (dating between 1832 and 1841) were opened primarily to relieve Central London's Anglican churchyards, many with later plots for other faiths such as at [[Highgate Cemetery]] where a number of international Jews of similar fame to some of those in the cemeteries below are buried. [[Brookwood Cemetery]], [[Surrey]], opened in 1852, designated approximately half of the original cemetery to non-Anglicans.\n\n==United Synagogue cemeteries==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! Name  !! Opened !! Borough  !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Alderney Road Jewish Cemetery \n| 1697\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]] \n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| 1852\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Also known as The Great Synagogue Burial Ground, this is Britain's oldest Ashkenazi cemetery.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/alderney-road-cemetery |title=Alderney Road Cemetery |website=[[United Synagogue]] |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/alderney-road-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Bancroft Road Jewish Cemetery \n| 1810\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]] \n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| 1907\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The Maiden Lane Synagogue constructed this cemetery on land formerly known as Globe Fields.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/bancroft-road-cemetery |title=Bancroft Road Cemetery |website=[[United Synagogue]] |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/bancroft-road-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Brady Street Cemetery]]\n| 1761\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n| [[E postcode area|E1]]\n| 1858\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The cemetery, no longer used, was originally the burial ground for the New Synagogue and was subsequently used by the [[Great Synagogue of London|Great Synagogue]].  Several notable people are buried there.\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Bushey Jewish Cemetery\n| 1947\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Borough of Hertsmere]], [[Hertfordshire]]\n|  [[WD postcode area|WD22]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <!-- Remarks -->\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/bushey-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | East Ham Jewish Cemetery\n| 1919\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[London Borough of Newham]]\n| [[E postcode area|E6]]\n| Yes\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | 110 servicemen and servicewomen from both world wars are buried here.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/38301/EAST%20HAM%20(MARLOW%20ROAD)%20JEWISH%20CEMETERY|title=East Ham (Marlow Road) Jewish Cemetery |website=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] |access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/east-ham-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Lauriston Road Cemetery \n| 1788\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Hackney]] \n| [[E postcode area|E9]]\n| 1886\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/lauriston-road-cemetery  Official website]\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Plashet Jewish Cemetery\n| 1896\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Newham]]\n| [[E postcode area|E6]]\n| Yes\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <!-- Remarks -->\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/plashet-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Waltham Abbey Jewish Cemetery\n| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Epping Forest District]] of [[Essex]]\n| [[EN postcode area|EN9]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | <!-- Remarks -->\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/waltham-abbey-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[West Ham Jewish Cemetery]]\n| 1856\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Newham]]\n| [[E postcode area|E15]]\n| Unknown\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | The cemetery was established by the New Synagogue on Great St Helen's, soon joined by the [[Great Synagogue of London|Great Synagogue]] in Duke's Place, both of them London congregations.<ref name= Kadish>[[Sharman Kadish|Kadish, Sharman]], ''Jewish Heritage in England : An Architectural Guide'', [[English Heritage]], 2006, p. 35</ref> There are a number of notable people buried here, in a graveyard visually dominated by the imposing [[Rothschild Mausoleum]].<ref name= Kadish/> One section contains graves removed to this burial place from the former [[Hoxton]] burial ground of the [[Hambro Synagogue]] when that site underwent urban redevelopment. The oldest legible tombstone in this section dates from 1794.<ref name= Kadish/>\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/west-ham-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Willesden Jewish Cemetery]]\n| 1873\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Brent]]\n| [[NW10]]\n| Yes\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |   It has been described as the \"Rolls Royce\" of London's Jewish cemeteries<ref name=\"70 years\">{{Cite web |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/whats-new/news/70-years-of-listing/ |title=New Listings Announced to Celebrate 70 Years of Protecting England's Historic Buildings |publisher=[[Historic England]] |access-date=8 May 2019}}</ref> and is designated Grade II on [[Historic England]]'s [[Register of Historic Parks and Gardens of special historic interest in England|Register of Historic Parks and Gardens]].<ref name=NHLEGarden>{{NHLE|num=1449184|desc=Willesden Jewish Cemetery (United Synagogue Cemetery)|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> In 2015 it was awarded a grant from the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]] to restore some key features of the cemetery and to create a visitor centre, a permanent exhibition and a web-based education project.<ref name=\"Facelift\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thejc.com/community/community-news/historic-cemetery-to-get-2m-heritage-facelift-1.61655 | title=Historic cemetery to get \u00a32m heritage facelift | work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]] | date=5 November 2015 | accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"JR Abrams\">{{Cite magazine |last=Abrams |first=Hester |date=July 2017 |title=Project breathes life into Willesden cemetery |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/587e46d129687f2d2ff30d8f/t/59e6482df9a61efdf89502f1/1508264055848/2017_03JUL.pdf |magazine=[[Jewish Renaissance]] |page=10 |access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref> Burial in existing family plots is available on request.\n| [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/willesden-cemetery Official website]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Federation cemeteries==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! Name !! Opened !! Borough !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Edmonton Jewish Cemetery\n| 1884\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[London Borough of Enfield]]\n| [[N postcode area|N18]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |  <!-- Remarks -->\n| [https://www.federation.org.uk/burial/cemeteries/  Official website]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Rainham Jewish Cemetery\n| 1938\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[London Borough of Havering]]\n| [[RM postcode area|RM13]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |  <!-- Remarks -->\n| [https://www.federation.org.uk/burial/cemeteries/  Official website]\n|-\n|}\n\n==West End Great Synagogue Burial Society cemeteries==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! Name !! Opened !! Borough  !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Streatham Park Cemetery#Streatham Jewish Cemetery|Streatham Jewish Cemetery]]\n| 1915\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Lambeth]]\n| [[SW postcode area|SW16]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | This is a section of Streatham Park Cemetery. The majority of burials here are those of [[Ashkenazi Jews]] of eastern European origin who settled in the Soho area of London and worked as tailors, cabinetmakers, shopkeepers, etc. A small section of Streatham Park Cemetery is reserved for members of the [[South London Liberal Synagogue]].<ref>[http://www.iajgs.org/cemetery/london/streatham-jewish-cemetery.html Streatham Jewish Cemetery - International Jewish Cemetery Project]</ref> This cemetery contains the Commonwealth war graves of 13 service personnel from World War II.\n| <!-- [URL Yes/No] or [[Articlename|Article]] -->\n|-\n|}\n\n==West London Synagogue cemeteries==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! Name !! Opened !! Borough  !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Balls Pond Road Cemetery]]\n| 1843\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Islington]]\n| [[N postcode area|N1]]\n| Yes\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Also known as Jewish (West London Reform) Cemetery, Kingsbury Road Cemetery, Balls Pond Burial Ground and The Jewish Burial Ground\n| [[Balls Pond Road Cemetery |Article]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Golders Green Jewish Cemetery]]\n| 1895\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Barnet]]\n| [[NW11]]\n| Yes\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Also known as Hoop Lane Jewish Cemetery, it is maintained by a joint burial committee representing members of the [[West London Synagogue]] and the S&P Sephardi Community (the Spanish and Portuguese Jews Congregation)\n| [http://www.hooplanecemetery.org.uk Official website]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Other cemeteries==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+\n! Name  !! Opened !! Borough  !! Postcode !! Closed !! Notes !! Website\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Brentwood Jewish Cemetery\n| 1974\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Borough of Brentwood]], [[Essex]]\n| Brentwood\n| 1974\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Contains c.7500 remains removed from Nuevo cemetery, London in 1974, according to a plaque near the entrance to a mass grave\n|  <!-- [URL Yes/No] or [[Articlename|Article]] -->\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Carterhatch Lane Jewish Cemetery\n| Unknown\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[London Borough of Enfield]]\n|  [[EN postcode area|EN1]]\n| No\n| style=\"text-align: