1\n|-\n|[[2014 J. League Division 2|2014]]||42||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|-||42||1\n|-\n|[[2015 J2 League|2015]]||8||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|-||8||0\n|-\n|[[2016 J1 League|2016]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Ventforet Kofu]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[J1 League]]||14||0||1||0||5||0||20||0\n|-\n|[[2017 J1 League|2017]]||33||0||0||0||3||0||36||0\n|-\n|[[2018 J1 League|2018]]||rowspan=\"1\"|[[J\u00fabilo Iwata]]||16||0||0||0||3||0||19||0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!128||2||1||0||11||0||140||2\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jubilo-iwata.co.jp/pages/tas/player/2018/04 Profile at J\u00fabilo Iwata]\n*{{J.League player|11312}}\n*{{Soccerway|ryo-shinzato/287246}}\n\n{{J\u00fabilo Iwata squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shinzato, Ryo}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chukyo University alumni]]\n[[Category:Association football people from Aichi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese footballers]]\n[[Category:J1 League players]]\n[[Category:J2 League players]]\n[[Category:Mito HollyHock players]]\n[[Category:Ventforet Kofu players]]\n[[Category:J\u00fabilo Iwata players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Japan-footy-defender-1990s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "TSUBAME98", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryo_Shinzato"}
{"title_page": "List of Neighbours characters (1988)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Neighbours'' characters (1988)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n''[[Neighbours]]'' is an Australian television soap opera that was first broadcast on 18 March 1985. The following is a list of characters that first appeared in the serial in 1988, by order of first appearance. Until February, characters were introduced by the soap's creator and executive producer, [[Reg Watson]]. Thereafter, they were introduced by his successor, [[Don Battye]]. The 4th season of ''Neighbours'' began airing from 13 January 1988. February saw the introduction of Sally Jensen and [[Kristian Schmid]] as siblings [[#Katie Landers|Katie Landers]] and [[#Todd Landers|Todd Landers]]. Comedian [[Greg Fleet]] began portraying criminal [[#Dave Summers|Dave Summers]] in March. [[Tom Oliver]] began playing [[#Lou Carpenter|Lou Carpenter]] in the same month.  [[#David Bishop|David Bishop]] arrived in May, as did [[#Amy Williams|Amy Williams]] and her mother [[#Nene Williams|Nina Williams]]. [[#John Worthington|John Worthington]] was introduced the following month. July saw the arrivals of [[#Bronwyn Davies|Bronwyn Davies]], played by [[Rachel Friend]], her sister [[#Sharon Davies|Sharon Davies]], played by Jessica Muschamp, and Mark Stevens as [[#Nick Page|Nick Page]]. [[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]] began playing [[Joe Mangel]], son of the established [[Nell Mangel]] from August. Irene Inescort arrived as Bronwyn and Sharon's aunt, [[#Edith Chubb|Edith Chubb]] in the same month. September saw the debut of [[#Sylvie Latham|Sylvie Latham]]. [[Mat Stevenson]] took on the role of [[#Skinner|Skinner]] in October, and Joe's son [[#Toby Mangel|Toby Mangel]] made his first appearance in November, as did [[Colin Handley]] as [[#Mark Granger|Mark Granger]].\n\n==Katie Landers==\n{{Main|Katie Landers}}\n'''Katie Landers''' played by Sally Jensen, made her first appearance on 15 February 1988. Jensen and [[Kristian Schmid]], who plays Katie's brother [[Todd Landers]], had not met before or had any acting experience until they attended a drama class with the Actor's Training Studio in Melbourne.<ref name=\"Friends\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Sally+Jensen+and+Neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=news890115_0017_9692|title=Friends and Neighbours|last=Wilson|first=George|date=15 January 1989|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Hopwood9\">[[#refhopwood|Hopwood 1990]], p.9.</ref> Scouts from the Grundy Organisation were also in attendance, on the look out for a pair of actors for ''Neighbours''.<ref name=\"Friends\"/> Jensen and Schmid attended an audition for the roles of regular characters, Katie and Todd, and following a screen test, they were cast.<ref name=\"Friends\"/><ref name=\"Hopwood9\"/> Both actors were at school when they were cast, so they were given an on set tutor and a schoolroom was built behind the studio.<ref name=\"Friends\"/> The BBC said Katie's most notable moment was \"Forcing Joe Mangel to bury a casserole.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_katielanders/page1|title=Character: Katie Landers|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031215121058/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_katielanders%2Fpage1|archivedate=15 December 2003|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' said Katie and Todd's escapades often portrayed storylines which were \"vital themes in the show.\"<ref name=\"Friends\"/>\n{{-}}\n\n==Todd Landers==\n{{Main|Todd Landers}}\n'''Todd Landers''', played by [[Kristian Schmid]], made his first appearance on 15 February 1988. Schmid was 12 years old when he signed himself up for an acting course in Melbourne.<ref name=\"Kid\">{{cite news|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/04/25/12990_gt_features.html|title=That Schmid kid|date=25 April 2008|work=[[Geelong Advertiser]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref> Three weeks later, ''Neighbours'' casting director [[Jan Russ]] came to the school to hold auditions for the show.<ref name=\"Kid\"/> Russ said she was looking for a teenage boy, around 14 or 15, to play the role of Todd Landers.<ref name=\"Kid\"/> Schmid asked to audition and he was cast in the role of Todd.<ref name=\"Kid\"/> Todd was [[Beverly Marshall]]'s (Lisa Armytage) \"cheekily independent nephew\".<ref name=\"Wallis64\">[[#refwallis|Wallis 1989]], p.64.</ref> He and his sister [[Katie Landers]] (Sally Jensen), come to live with Beverly and her husband [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] ([[Alan Dale]]) in [[Ramsay Street]] in order to escape their abusive father.<ref name=\"Wallis64\"/> Schmid remained with ''Neighbours'' until his character was killed off at the age of 17,<ref name=\"Kid\"/> making him the youngest character in the show's history to die.<ref name=\"orange\">{{cite web|title=Neighbours stars: where are they now?|url=http://www.orange.co.uk/entertainment/television/pics/3468_4.htm?linkfrom=entertainment_television_pics_3468_5&link=link_back&article=neighboursstarswherearetheynow|work=[[Orange (telecommunications)|Orange.co.uk]]|publisher=([[France T\u00e9l\u00e9com]])|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref>\nIn 2007, Australian newspaper the ''[[Herald Sun]]'' placed Todd's death at number ten on their list of ''Neighbours'' Top Ten moments.<ref name=\"Moments\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/your-all-time-favourite-moment/story-e6frf99f-1111113933908|title=Your all-time favourite moment|date=11 July 2007|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=Herald and Weekly Times|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Dave Summers==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Dave Summers\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = [[Greg Fleet]]\n| first          = {{start date|1988|3|25|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1988|5|2|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#S|Former; guest]]\n}}\n'''Dave Summers''' played by [[Greg Fleet]], made his first appearance on 25 March 1988. The character was introduced alongside [[#Ted Regan|Ted Regan]] (Julian Branagan) as new villains for the serial.<ref name=\"K52\">[[#refkercher|Kercher 1989]], p.52.</ref> Fleet's character is best known for causing the death of popular character [[Daphne Clarke]] ([[Elaine Smith (actress)|Elaine Smith]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standup.com.au/comedian/greg-fleet|title=Greg Fleet|publisher=The Sit Down Comedy Club|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> When asked about his character's actions, Fleet responded: \"Do I feel bad about killing Daphne on ''Neighbours''? If you are going to be in a show as bad as ''Neighbours'', you should kill one of the main characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thatsmags.com/shanghai/post/24447/greg-fleet|title=Comedian Greg Fleet on His Sociopathic Father Faking His Death|date=1 August 2018|work=That's Magazine|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> In Fleet's biography ''These Things Happen'', he tells of how his role prevented him from having his throat cut in a drug deal gone wrong, as the dealer recognised him from the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/books-magazines/books/these-things-happen-six-shocking-stories-from-greg-fleets-memoir/news-story/e6d6077f9db41c882522a19e1124001c|first=Andrew|last=Bucklow|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=12 October 2018|title=These Things Happen\u2019: Six shocking stories from Greg Fleet's memoir|publisher=[[news.com.au]]}}</ref> Series writer [[Marieke Hardy]] described Fleet's role as \"small but important\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/more-power-to-new-neighbours-20070802-ge5hcc.html|title= More Power to new Neighbours|first=Marieke|last=Hardy|date= 2 August 2007|accessdate=11 July 2019|work= [[The Age]]}}</ref> Prior to playing Summers, Fleet guested as Steve O'Donnel on the serial in 1985.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 50|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Russell Webb; Writer: Craig Wilkins|network=[[Seven Network]]|airdate=24 May 1985}}</ref> \n \nSummers and his friend Ted Regan run Daphne Clarke and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]]'s ([[Fiona Corke]]) car off the road, causing a crash which leaves Gail with amnesia and Daphne in a coma for several weeks. Summers and Regan are caught by [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]]), [[Charlene Robinson]] ([[Kylie Minogue]]), [[Tony Romeo (Neighbours)|Tony Romeo]] ([[Nick Carrafa]]), [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] ([[Alan Dale]]) and [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]) when their car is spotted at Lassiter's by Gail, who recalls the license plate via hypnosis. Daphne dies as a result of her injuries and Summers and Regan are both tried, but Summers only receives a one year suspension of his license and a $500 fine, which enrages [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] ([[Guy Pearce]]). Mike goes after Summers and Regan to fight them, but does not. Summers then reports Mike to the police and he is charged with assault, despite being innocent. Mike is then found guilty of simple assault, but not GBH.\n{{-}}\n\n==Lou Carpenter==\n{{Main|Lou Carpenter}}\n'''Lou Carpenter''', played by [[Tom Oliver]], made his first appearance on 30 March 1988. Oliver appeared for a brief time, having been initially contracted for six months, before leaving and returning in January 1992 as a regular cast member.<ref>{{cite episode|url=|title=This Morning \u2013 Tuesday 25th September|episodelink=|series=This Morning|serieslink=This Morning (TV programme)|credits=Schofield, Phillip; Willoughby, Holly; Oliver, Tom|network=[[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]|airdate=25 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/neighbours/a151395/tom-oliver-lou-carpenter-neighbours/|title=Tom Oliver (Lou Carpenter, 'Neighbours')|first=David|last=Balls|date=7 April 2009|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> He would go on to become one of the longest-serving continuous characters.<ref name=\"OK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ok.co.uk/lifestyle/view/56201/Interview-Tom-Oliver-and-Chris-Milligan/|title=Interview: Tom Oliver and Chris Milligan|date=16 November 2012|work=[[OK!]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> Lou was introduced as an old friend of [[Harold Bishop]] ([[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]) and [[Madge Bishop|Madge Ramsay]] ([[Anne Charleston]]). In their fictional backstory, the characters attended the same school and Lou was Harold's rival for Madge's affections. Oliver said that Lou's feelings for Madge led him to visit Ramsay Street to steal her from Harold on their wedding day.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> Oliver took inspiration for Lou's distinctive \"dirty laugh\" from actor [[Sid James]].<ref name=\"OK\"/> The character also became known for his scams and quick one-liners.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=12\u201325 May 2001|title=Hooked on a feeling|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|issue=179|page=16}}</ref> Oliver received nominations for Funniest Performance at the 2007 and 2008 [[Inside Soap Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/scoop/a64083/inside-soap-awards-2007-the-nominations.html|first=Kris|last=Green|title=Inside Soap Awards 2007: The Nominations|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=3 July 2007|accessdate=4 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://msnuktvsoaps.spaces.live.com/blog/cns!E65397F19A3BDCEA!3110.entry|title=Inside Soap Awards 2008 \u2013 Nominations|date=16 July 2008|publisher=[[MSN TV]]|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==David Bishop==\n{{Main|David Bishop (Neighbours)}}\n'''David Bishop''', played by [[Kevin Harrington (actor)|Kevin Harrington]], made his first appearance during the episode broadcast on 11 May 1988, arriving for his father [[Harold Bishop]]'s ([[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]) wedding.<ref name=\"Miller\"/> Harrington returned to ''Neighbours'' after a 16-year absence in October 2003.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=kevin+harrington+and+neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE030724UUF5V67V1D5|title=Networking|last=Miller|first=Kylie|date=24 July 2003|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=kevin+harrington+and+neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE030515TIIHK0IBD25|title=Networking|last=Miller|first=Kylie|date=15 May 2003|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref> The character, his wife and daughter were written out in 2005, as part of a \"surprise shake-up\" of the cast.<ref name=\"StarsAxed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a21089/three-top-neighbours-stars-axed.html|title=Three top 'Neighbours' stars axed|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|date=8 May 2005|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref> A writer for the [[BBC]]'s ''Neighbours'' website stated that David's most notable moment was \"Getting himself into financial trouble and keeping it a secret.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_davidbishop/page1|title=Character: David Bishop|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=16 July 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040715085004/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_davidbishop%2Fpage1|archivedate=15 July 2004|url-status=live}}</ref> Brian Courtis from ''The Age'' branded David \"Harold's hapless offspring\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=kevin+harrington+and+neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE050509C67KM6APP8T|title=Coming clean while the soap suds swirl|last=Courtis|first=Brian|date=9 May 2005|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Nene Williams==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Nene Williams\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = Leigh Morgan (1988)<br />[[Ally Fowler]] (2016)\n| first          = {{start date|1988|5|25|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|2016|4|12|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]] (1988)<br />[[Jason Herbison]] (2016)\t \n| years          = 1988, 2016\n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#W|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation     = Stewardess<br>Businesswoman<br />Nurse\n| alias          = Nina Williams\n| husband        = Bruce (divorced)\n| daughters      = [[Amy Williams (Neighbours)|Amy Williams]]\n| grandsons      = [[Jimmy Williams (Neighbours)|Jimmy Williams]]\n}}\n'''Nene Williams''' (also '''Nina Williams''') made her first appearance on 25 May 1988. She was originally played by Leigh Morgan. When the character was reintroduced in 2016, [[Ally Fowler]] took over the role. Fowler previously appeared in ''Neighbours'' as [[Zoe Davis]].<ref name=\"JMoran\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/ally-fowler-has-not-been-on-the-set-of-neighbours-for-30-years-but-will-cause-chaos-on-her-return/news-story/4b13d5d166dacca8df23858a8229bc06?nk=cfb429b18655ca0e93ccfee99540e4e4-1456243710|title=Ally Fowler has not been on the set of Neighbours for 30 years but will cause chaos on her return|last=Moran|first=Jonathon|date=23 February 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref> She commented, \"It's not difficult to go full circle on ''Neighbours''. The writers are very clever with the way that they can link people together. I love being back with Stefan again, we're having a lot of fun.\"<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> Fowler admitted to some apprehension about joining the cast again, as she likes to move forward, but knowing the role was short term, she thought it would be fun.<ref name=\"SEllis\">{{cite magazine|last=Ellis|first=Sarah|date=26 March \u2013 1 April 2016|title='Kissing Paul Robinson? I was smooching his dad 30 years ago!'|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|issue=12|page=31}}</ref> Fowler began filming in late 2015,<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> and began appearing from 29 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/show-news/ally-fowler-returns-to-neighbours|title=Ally Fowler returns to Neighbours|date=23 February 2016|publisher=[[Tenplay]]|accessdate=12 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160227062905/http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/show-news/ally-fowler-returns-to-neighbours|archivedate=27 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nNene is [[Amy Williams (Neighbours)|Amy Williams]]'s ([[Zoe Cramond]]) mother, and former partner of [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]), who she met while she was an air stewardess.<ref name=\"McLennan\"/> Upon her return, she \"immediately ruffles feathers\" when she sets her sights on one of the married characters,<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> later confirmed to be [[Karl Kennedy]] ([[Alan Fletcher (actor)|Alan Fletcher]]) after he rescues her during a heatwave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/neighbours/a784173/neighbours-spoiler-steph-suffers-a-tragic-relapse-while-at-mediation/|title=Neighbours Spoiler: Steph suffers a tragic relapse while at mediation|first=Daniel|last=Kilkelly|date=20 February 2016|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> [[Network Ten]] drama executive Claire Tonkin called Nene \"complex\" and stated: \"from her first moments on Ramsay Street, this character promises intrigue, secrets and lots of drama\".<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> Of her character's reasons for coming to Erinsborough, Fowler explained that Nene is angry with Paul for not helping her or being a proper father to Amy over the years.<ref name=\"McLennan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/neighbours/neighbours-news/neighbours-ally-fowler-reveals-why-she-cant-keep-away-from-paul-robinson-video-329141/|title=Neighbours' Ally Fowler reveals why she can't keep away from Paul Robinson|last=McLennan|first=Patrick|date=12 April 2016|work=[[What's on TV]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> She said, \"I think there's a desperate need in [Nene] to have family and to experience what having a family would be like and have that support, so in that way she craves Paul's support.\"<ref name=\"McLennan\"/> Fowler also said that Paul would end up using Nene for his own gain.<ref name=\"McLennan\"/>\n\nWhen her grandson [[Jimmy Williams (Neighbours)|Jimmy Williams]] (Darcy Tadich) is injured playing cricket, Nene makes some questionable choices while treating him, leading Amy to ask Karl for a second opinion. Nene feels that Amy does not trust her, and Fowler explained to an ''[[Inside Soap]]'' writer that Nene suffers from anxiety.<ref name=\"Danger\">{{cite magazine|date=12\u201318 March 2016|title=Doug in danger?|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|issue=10|page=31}}</ref> She continued, \"She's had a few problems in the past with her career \u2013 she's got involved with the odd doctor that she shouldn't have, which hasn't ended well \u2013 and she's had to play with the truth a little bit so that Amy doesn't worry.\"<ref name=\"Danger\"/> Knowing that Karl and Amy are watching her, she invents a crisis with [[Doug Willis]] ([[Terence Donovan (actor)|Terence Donovan]]), who she is caring for.<ref name=\"Danger\"/> Nene and Paul later share a kiss, and Nene enjoys playing \"happy families\" with him, Amy and Jimmy. She finds it comforting, but is unaware that Paul has an ulterior motive.<ref name=\"SEllis\"/>\n\nNina organises a [[women in the workplace]] conference at Lassiter's Hotel in [[Erinsborough]], and brings her young daughter Amy with her. She befriends [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] ([[Fiona Corke]]) and invites her to give a talk at the conference when Gail mentions she is married to her boss. Nina is surprised to learn that Gail's husband is Paul Robinson, who she once dated while they worked for the same airline. Gail invites Nina to dinner with her and Paul, but Nina declines the invitation. Paul seeks her out and asks about her life. She explains that she started her own business, fell pregnant with Amy and will be getting married soon. Paul soon works out that Amy is his daughter. Nina tells him that she did not know she was pregnant until after their break up. She also tells him that her fianc\u00e9 Bruce already thinks of Amy as his own and she is leaving that day. Paul asks to be a part of Amy's life, but Nina refuses. Gail tells Nina that Amy might be the only child Paul has. Before she leaves, Nina visits Paul to tells him that she will send him photos of Amy, as well as allowing him to set up a trust fund for Amy's education. Several years later, when Nina and Bruce go through marital problems, Nina sends Amy to live with Paul in Erinsborough for a few months after he visits her in [[New Zealand]].\n\nOver twenty years later, Nina, now calling herself Nene, returns to Erinsborough in the middle of a massive heatwave. She meets her grandson, Jimmy Williams and goes for walk with him, but collapses due to the extreme heat. Karl Kennedy finds Nene and gets her safely to hospital. Amy visits Nene and wants to know what she is doing in town. Nene tells her she has quit her nursing job in Mount Merrion and moved to Erinsborough for a fresh start. Nene develops feelings for Karl, who she assumes is single, but he tells her he is married. Nene is discharged from hospital and stays with Amy and Jimmy at Number 26, along with Amy's boyfriend [[Kyle Canning]] ([[Chris Milligan]]) and his family. Amy asks Karl if there are any nursing jobs available at the hospital and Karl agrees to meet with Nene. Nene discloses that she left her previous job because she had an affair with a doctor who blamed her for a mistake after they split. When the arranged interview falls through, Karl arranges for Nene to be Alzheimer's sufferer Doug Willis' carer.\n\nIn her new position, Nene manipulates situations to spend more time with Karl by lying about Doug's mood swings and calls Karl during a birthday lunch much to the irritation of his wife, [[Susan Kennedy]] ([[Jackie Woodburne]]). She also begins confusing Doug by claiming she is his wife [[Pam Willis]] ([[Sue Jones (actress)|Sue Jones]]), uses Karl's laptop to delete an email from a former colleague, and tracks correspondence between Kyle and his former wife, [[Georgia Brooks]] ([[Saskia Hampele]]). However, Doug is able to see through her act and tells the Kennedys, who confront Nene about her erratic behaviour. Nene admits that she has not been taking her anti-depressant medication. Doug agrees not to report Nene, as he knows what it is like to lose control of his own mind. Following this, Nene turns to Paul for support and falls for him again. When she tries to kiss him, Paul rebuffs Nene and lets her down gently. When an explosion occurs at Lassiter's hotel, Nene puts on a nurse's uniform and attempts to treat a comatose [[Jack Callahan (Neighbours)|Jack Callaghan]] ([[Andrew Morley]]), but Doug's granddaughter, [[Paige Smith]] ([[Olympia Valance]]) recognises her and she flees. When Paul is accused of causing the explosion, he asks Nene to provide an alibi for him and she does so, but retracts it when she sees Paul kissing [[Terese Willis]] ([[Rebekah Elmaloglou]]). She then leaves Erinsborough to stay in a retreat in the Blue Mountains and receives treatment for her condition.\n\n==Amy Williams==\n{{Main|Amy Williams (Neighbours)}}\n'''Amy Williams''' (previously '''Robinson''') made her first appearance on 25 May 1988. She was originally played by Nicolette Minster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/review-louise-joy-mccrae-nicolette-minster-in-girls-uninterrupted/story-fncv4qxa-1226314838646|title=Review: Louise Joy McCrae, Nicolette Minister in Girls Uninterrupted|first=Matthew|last=Schultz|date=30 March 2012|accessdate=10 August 2014|work=[[Herald Sun]]}}</ref> Minster was around three years old when she was cast in the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/mediaflash/docs/ob_28aug13_az/4|title=On target for more laughs|last=Richardson|first=Mark|date=28 August 2013|work=The Melbourne Observer via [[Issuu]]|page=4|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> Amy was introduced to ''Neighbours'' as the first child of established character [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]).<ref>[[#refmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.16.</ref> When the character returned to the show in 1992, Sheridan Compagnino took over the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_amyrobinson/page1|title=Character: Amy Robinson|publisher=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=14 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050409050618/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_amyrobinson%2Fpage1|archivedate=9 April 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> Amy was reintroduced to ''Neighbours'' with actress [[Zoe Cramond]] taking over the role in 2015.<ref name=\"AllChange\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s14/neighbours/news/a647877/all-change-for-neighbours-four-new-regulars-join-the-soaps-cast.html#~pcYKylGLFjEg03|title=All change for Neighbours: Four new regulars join the soap's cast|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=17 May 2015|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> Cramond described Amy as \"very straightforward yet quite complex\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/features/zoe-cramond-joins-neighbours|title=Zoe Cramond joins Neighbours|date=4 June 2015|publisher=[[Network Ten]]|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> A ''Soap World'' contributor branded her \"mysteriously sexy and tomboyish\".<ref>{{cite magazine|date=July 2015|title=Come to grandpa!|magazine=Soap World|issue=270|page=19}}</ref>\n\n==John Worthington==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name = John Worthington\n| series = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer = [[Brian James (actor)|Brian James]]\n| first = {{start date|1988|6|9|df=y}}\n| last = {{end date|1988|10|24|df=y}}\n| introducer = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#W|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation = Retired dentist\n| wife = Iris Worthington (until 1987)<br />[[Nell Mangel]] (1988\u2013; his death)\n| daughters = Caroline Worthington\n}}\n'''John Worthington''', played by [[Brian James (actor)|Brian James]], made his first appearance on 9 June 1988.<ref name=\"Devlyn\">{{cite journal|last=Devlyn|first=Darren|date=15 October 1988|title=Nell bowls up to the altar|journal=[[TV Week]]|pages=8\u20139}}</ref> The character was introduced as a love interest for [[Nell Mangel]] ([[Vivean Gray]]). He and Nell become bowling colleagues and share \"a strong and mutual need for love and companionship.\"<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/> The couple soon become engaged. Shortly before the wedding, Nell has second thoughts, while John needs reassurance from [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] ([[Paul Keane]]) and [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]).<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/> James commented, \"He does have a few anxious moments before Nell arrives.\"<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/> Nell and John became the third couple to marry in 1988.<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/>\n\nJohn is a widowed, retired dentist. He meets Nell Mangel when she joins the local bowls team. There is an attraction between them, but their relationship breaks down when John tires of Nell's gossipy ways. However, John reappears several months later and they get reacquainted. Nell's son, [[Joe Mangel]] ([[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]]) takes a dislike to John and throws him out of the house. Joe later warms to John and gives him his blessing to marry Nell. When a 30-year-old letter written by John's late wife Iris reveals his infidelity, Nell breaks off the engagement. But she eventually realises John's affair was a long time ago and the wedding goes ahead. John and Nell bid farewell to all their friends in Erinsborough and relocate to [[St. Albans]]. When Nell's granddaughter, [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]])  returns to Erinsborough in 2018, she mentions that John has since died.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Bronwyn Davies==\n{{Main|Bronwyn Davies}}\n'''Bronwyn Davies''' played by [[Rachel Friend]]. She made her first appearance on 7 July 1988. Following [[Kylie Minogue]]'s ([[Charlene Robinson]]) departure, the ''Neighbours'' producers were about to begin a nation-wide search for a new female actress to join the show, when they discovered Friend.<ref name=\"NewNeighbour\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rachel+Friend+and+Neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=news880625_0183_0393|title=Your New Neighbour|date=25 June 1988|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|page=51|accessdate=6 June 2011}}</ref> Friend chose to postpone her university degree to join ''Neighbours'' as country girl, Bronwyn Davies.<ref name=\"NewNeighbour\"/> In 1990, Friend decided to quit the serial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/TV--Radio/Role-of-honour/2005/03/13/1110649050747.html|title=Role of honour|last=Idato|first=Michael|date=14 March 2005|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=14 September 2010}}</ref> For her portrayal of Bronwyn, Friend won \"Most Popular Actress\" at the 1990 [[Logie Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1990 TV Week Logie Awards|url=http://tvweek.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=732945&showcomments=true|work=[[TV Week]]|publisher=[[Ninemsn]]|accessdate=13 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324005436/http://tvweek.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=732945&showcomments=true|archive-date=24 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> During a feature on past ''Neighbours'' characters, telecommunications network [[Orange (telecommunications)|Orange]], described Bronwyn's most memorable moment as: \"Accidentally pushing good pal Henry Ramsay (played by Craig McLachlan) down some steps. Believing the mulleted larrikin was unconscious, Bronwyn rushed to his side and professed her undying love for him \u2013 whereupon Henry opened his eyes and admitted he felt the same. Aaah!\"<ref name=\"orange\"/>\n\n==Nick Page==\n{{Main|Nick Page}}\n'''Nick Page''', played by Mark Stevens, made his first appearance on 22 July 1988. Stevens joined the cast of ''Neighbours'' soon after taking part in ''[[Young Talent Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=Tony|title=What a soap buster|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=mark+stevens&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=1month&sd=01%2F01%2F1987&ed=01%2F01%2F1996&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&docID=news890702_0157_1723|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=([[Fairfax Media]])|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=2 July 1989}}</ref> Stevens' first scene consisted of Nick trying to find his stolen [[Walkman]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Neighbours the whole story|magazine=[[Fast Forward (magazine)|Fast Forward]]|date=1-7 August 1990|issue=47|publisher=[[BBC Magazines]]}}</ref> Josephine Monroe, author of ''Neighbours: the first 10 years'' described Nick as one [[Helen Daniels]]' ([[Anne Haddy]]) many waifs and strays, a budding artist and having a recalcitrant personality.<ref>[[#refmmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.42.</ref><ref>[[#refmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.98.</ref> The BBC described Nick's most notable moment as being \"his first appearance when he was caught spraying graffiti\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_nickpage/page1|title=Character: Nick Page|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=23 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The episode featuring Nick rescuing Todd and Katie from Skinner was watched by 21 million viewers in the United Kingdom. It was the most watched episode of any show during 1990.<ref>{{cite web|title=BARB Since 1981|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/facts/since1981?year=1990&view=top10|work=barb.co.uk|publisher=([[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]])|accessdate=23 February 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622023437/http://www.barb.co.uk/facts/since1981?year=1990&view=top10|archivedate=22 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Sharon Davies==\n{{Main|Sharon Davies}}\n'''Sharon Davies''', played by Jessica Muschamp, made her first appearance on 29 July 1988. Muschamp landed the role while completing her [[Victorian Certificate of Education|VCE]] in 1988.<ref name=\"TheAge\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/arts/2010/02/27/1266687178528.html?page=2|title=That was then, this is now \u2013 Jessica Muschamp|date=28 February 2010|work=The Age |location=Australia|publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref> Muschamp said she thought the audition would be a good experience and that she did not expect to get the role.<ref name=\"Hopwood47\">[[#refhopwood|Hopwood 1990]], p.47.</ref> During her time with ''Neighbours'', Muschamp said she \"had a ball\" working with the other members of the cast.<ref name=\"TheAge\"/> Sharon is described as a \"impetuous, laid back character.\"<ref name=\"Special\">{{Cite book|last=Hopwood|first=Clive|title=Neighbours Special|year=1990|publisher=World International Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-0-7235-6895-7|page=16}}</ref> She is bubbly, but tactless. Sharon often insults people, but she does not mean to and she can be a little thoughtless.<ref name=\"Special\"/> In 1990, during a cast exodus, producers decided to send the character to New Zealand.<ref name=\"TheAge\"/> In ''Neighbours: The Official Annual 1991'', authors John McCready and Nicola Furlong said Muschamp had made her mark on ''Neighbours''. They added \"The love lives of those such as Nick Page and Sharon Davies have made the programme perhaps the most popular viewing for teenagers around the world.\"<ref>[[#refmccready|McCready 1990]], p.19, 59.</ref>\n\n==Joe Mangel==\n{{Main|Joe Mangel}}\n'''Joe Mangel''', played by [[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]], made his first appearance on 8 August 1988.<ref name=\"Identity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/mark-little2/accidental-fame-of-an-anarchist_b_6807628.html|title=Mangel'd: The Accidental Fame of an Anarchist Or How an Aussie Soap Character Stole my Identity|last=Little|first=Mark|date=5 March 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post|The Huffington Post UK]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> Little was initially contracted for 13 weeks,<ref name=\"MakingMark\">{{cite magazine|last=Devlyn|first=Darren|date=6 August 1988|title=Making his Mark|magazine=[[TV Week]]|page=25}}</ref> but this was soon extended.<ref name=\"Identity\"/> Joe is the estranged son of [[Nell Mangel]] ([[Vivean Gray]]).<ref name=\"MakingMark\"/> Very little was known about Joe prior to his introduction, and Darren Devlyn branded him \"an unknown quantity in Erinsborough\".<ref name=\"MakingMark\"/> Joe is nothing like his mother, and he was described as being an \"unreconstructed oaf who likes drinking beer\", green fingered and brutish. Nell and [[Dorothy Burke]] ([[Maggie Dence]]) attempt to make Joe change his ways, and he often clashes with his niece [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]]).<ref>[[#refmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.79\u201380.</ref> Little chose to leave the serial in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal|title=It's time to move on|journal=[[TV Week]]|date=4\u201310 May 1991}}</ref> Lorna Cooper, editor of [[MSN|MSN TV]], branded Joe one of show's legendary characters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tv.uk.msn.com/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=149729015&page=35|title=TV's Neighbours: where are they now?|publisher=[[MSN]]|author=Cooper, Lorna|date=17 March 2010|accessdate=14 July 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vwX2EQK1?url=http://tv.uk.msn.com/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=149729015&page=35|archivedate=23 January 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> While the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'s'' Polly Hudson chose Joe as one of her favourite characters, citing his \"funny, sweet and ute-obsessed\" personality and comedy moments as her reasons why.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/08/03/vote-for-your-favourite-soap-star-in-the-new-mirror-soap-awards-115875-21566830/|title=Vote for your favourite soap star in the new Mirror Soap Awards|last=Hudson|first=Polly|date=3 August 2009|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=14 July 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vwWyyyFG?url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/08/03/vote-for-your-favourite-soap-star-in-the-new-mirror-soap-awards-115875-21566830/|archivedate=23 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Edith Chubb==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Edith Chubb\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = Irene Inescort\n| first          = {{start date|1988|8|10|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1989|2|24|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| years          = 1988\u20131989\n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#C|Former; recurring]]\n| brothers       = Gordon Davies\n| nieces         = [[Bronwyn Davies]]<br />[[Sharon Davies]]\n| nephews        = Bill Davies\n}}\n'''Edith \"Edie\" Chubb''', played by Irene Inescort, made her first appearance on 10 August 1988 and departed on 24 February 1989. Edie is the aunt of [[Bronwyn Davies]] ([[Rachel Friend]]) and [[Sharon Davies]] (Jessica Muschamp).<ref>[[#refmonroe2|Monroe 1994]], p.209.</ref> She purchases [[Ramsay Street#No. 30|Number 30 Ramsay Street]] and moves in with her nieces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shortlist.com/news/neighbours-ramsay-street-house-up-for-sale|title=Neighbours' Ramsay Street house up for sale|work=[[Shortlist]]|date=24 January 2013|accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref> [[Grace Dent]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented that Edie had an echo of ''[[Coronation Street]]'s'' [[Ena Sharples]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/jul/30/tvandradio.theguide|first=Grace|last=Dent|title=Crowned with Glory|date=30 July 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nEdie arrives in Erinsborough in the middle of a Murder Mystery party her nieces Bronwyn and Sharon are attending. She tries to take Sharon back to [[Narrabri]], but she refuses to leave, so Edie allows the girls to stay with [[Nell Mangel]] ([[Vivean Gray]]). Sharon learns Edie is planning to buy Number 30 and that she has asked [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] (Paul Keane) to be a proxy bidder for her. Sharon tries to derail the auction by disguising herself as an elderly woman and attempting to drive the price up. Sharon succeeds, but Des quickly sees through the ruse and Sharon's bid is voided, and Edie buys the house. When Edie returns several weeks later, she is unimpressed to find Bronwyn and Sharon kissing their respective boyfriends [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] ([[Guy Pearce]]) and [[Nick Page]] (Mark Stevens). Edie then moves the girls in with her and tries to control their lives, but Sharon manages to manipulate Edie into letting her see Nick when she gets stuck in a tree attempting to rescue her cat, Arthur.\n\nEdie is less than pleased when Bronwyn begins dating [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] ([[Craig McLachlan]]), but is delighted when they break up, however, she is horrified when they reconcile. Edie also embarks on a feud with neighbour [[Joe Mangel]] ([[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]]). This culminates in Joe playing a practical joke by sending a [[marijuana]] plant to Number 30, resulting in Edie's arrest. Bent on revenge, Edie assists Joe's ex-wife [[#Noeline Mangel|Noeline Mangel]] (Lindy McConchie) in snatching their son [[Toby Mangel]] (Finn Greentree-Keane) from Joe, who he is currently staying with. This move endangers Toby as his violent stepfather, Ted Vickers (John Jacobs) attacks him and Noeline, but Joe saves them in the nick of time. Edie apologises to Joe as she had no idea of Ted's violent nature. Soon after, she leaves Erinsborough to look after a sick relative.\n{{-}}\n\n==Sylvie Latham==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| name           = Sylvie Latham\n| portrayer      = Christine Harris\n| first          = {{start date|1988|9|22|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1988|9|27|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#S|Former; guest]]\n| occupation     = Model\n}}\n'''Sylvie Latham''', played by Christine Harris, made her first appearance on 22 September 1988. Kesta Desmond author of ''Neighbours Special'', commented that Sylvie made a dramatic entrance to the show, as within one episode she had decided to \"romantically tackle\" [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott Robinson]] ([[Jason Donovan]]).<ref name=\"D33\">[[#refdesmond|Desmond 1990]], p.33.</ref> Desmond said Sylvie's method of seduction was \"far from subtle!\"<ref name=\"D33\"/> Of her role, Desmond stated: \"It caused quite a stir filming those scenes, but it was a lot of fun.\"<ref name=\"D33\"/> She thought she would get \"a lot of flack\" from fans of Scott, but she was surprised when she did not receive many complaints.<ref name=\"D33\"/>\n\nSylvie is a model who works for the same agency as [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]]). Scott Robinson interviews Sylvie at Jane's suggestion for his article for the ''Erinsborough News''. Sylvie and Scott have lunch and she is clearly attracted to him. When Sylvie admits that she is attracted to Scott, Jane warns her off and tells her that Scott is married to her friend [[Charlene Robinson]] ([[Kylie Minogue]]), who is currently in [[Brisbane]]. Undeterred, Sylvie steps up her quest to seduce Scott, who rebuffs her advances. Angry with being rejected, Sylvie lies to Jane that Scott spent the night with her at Lassiter's. Scott denies this and he and Jane confront Sylvie, who admits that she did it for attention because she felt like  she always had to live in her sister's shadow. She apologises to Scott.\n\n==Skinner==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Skinner\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = [[Mat Stevenson]]\n| first          = {{start date|1988|10|31|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1989|4|19|df=y}}\n| introducer      = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| years           = 1988\u20131989\n| classification  = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#S|Former; recurring]]\n}}\n'''Skinner''', played by [[Mat Stevenson]] made his first appearance on 31 October and departed on 19 April 1989.\nIn a 2005 interview with the BBC celebrating 20 years of Neighbours, Stevenson opined that serial's success was due to its cheerfulness \"There's a fair amount of optimism, youthful exuberance and the sunshine that just appeals.\" <ref name=\"Decades\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4358995.stm|title=Two decades with the Neighbours|first=Phill|last=Mercer|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> He added \"It is 15 years since I've been on the show but I still get recognised as Skinner. Last year I was travelling on a train in Melbourne and I signed 40 autographs. It's amazing how revered I am in other walks of life. Being in Neighbours has done me nothing but favours.\"<ref name= \"Decades\"/>\n\nSkinner meets [[Todd Landers]] ([[Kristian Schmid]]) at a local arcade when he runs away from home. When [[Helen Daniels]] ([[Anne Haddy]]) and [[Nick Page]] (Mark Stevens) come looking for Todd, Skinner lies and tells them he saw him at another arcade. He then invites Todd back to his squat and teaches him how to \"survive\" on the streets by stealing. Skinner gives Todd an ultimatum; either earn his keep or go back onto the streets. Todd reluctantly complies with Skinner's plan to rob a carphone warehouse. They go to a warehouse but when they spot Helen and Nick they run off. On the night of the robbery, Nick catches up with Skinner and Todd and fights with Skinner but is arrested when the alarm is triggered and Skinner gets away. Skinner warns Todd not to say anything. Feeling guilty, Todd flees while Skinner is asleep and returns home in order to exonerate Nick.\n\nSkinner turns up on Ramsay Street and plans to rob Number 22, forcing Todd to be his accomplice but Todd's sister, [[Katie Landers|Katie]] (Sally Jensen) catches him in the act and he threatens her. Fearful for his sister's safety, Todd unhooks [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]) and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]]'s ([[Fiona Corke]]) VCR. Gail arrives home unexpectedly and rescues Katie and Todd chases after Skinner. A passing Nick helps overpower Skinner and he is arrested. Several months later, Skinner reappears when Nick and his girlfriend [[Sharon Davies]] (Jessica Muschamp) hitch a lift back to Erinsborough after running away. He drives off with Sharon causing her to panic but offers to take her back to Erinsborough and she thanks him with a kiss. Skinner and Sharon begin dating much to Nick's horror and everyone tries to warn Sharon about Skinner but she will not listen. The final straw comes when Skinner menaces Sharon's older sister, [[Bronwyn Davies|Bronwyn]] ([[Rachel Friend]]) and attempts to force himself on her but Sharon catches him in the act. Skinner is then arrested once again.\n{{-}}\n\n==Toby Mangel==\n{{Main|Toby Mangel}}\n'''Toby Mangel''' made his first appearance on 10 November 1988. He was originally played by Finn Greentree-Keane until 1990.<ref name=\"Where\">{{cite magazine|date=8\u201321 December 2001|title=Where are they now? - Ben Geurens|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|publisher=Attic Futura (UK) Ltd|issue=194|page=71}}</ref> Ben Geurens then took over the role when Greentree-Keane decided to leave.<ref name=\"Where\"/> Geurens had previously done a stunt on ''Neighbours'' the year before with the New Generation Stunts company and had doubled for some of the other children.<ref name=\"Where\"/> When the producers needed a new actor to play the part of Toby they thought Geurens would be ideal as he already had experience with the show.<ref name=\"Where\"/> Guerens remained in the serial until 1993.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Home+truths.-a0137900710|title=Home truths|last=Whitfield|first=Graeme|date=25 October 2005|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref> A writer for the BBC said Toby's most notable moment was \"coping with his mother and Kerry's deaths\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_tobymangel/page1|title=Character: Toby Mangel|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=1 April 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050413194314/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_tobymangel%2Fpage1|archivedate=13 April 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> A columnist for ''Inside Soap'' called Toby \"the cutest child on Ramsay Street\" and said he became a favourite with viewers.<ref name=\"Where\"/> \n{{-}}\n\n==Mark Granger==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Mark Granger\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = [[Colin Handley]]\n| first          = {{start date|1988|11|23|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1989|2|9|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#G|Former;recurring]]\n| father         = Mark Granger\n| mother         = Mrs Granger\n| grandfathers    = Mark Granger\n| years          = 1988\u20131989\n| occupation     = Businessman\n\n}}\n'''Mark Granger''' played by [[Colin Handley]], made his first appearance on 23 November 1988 and departed on 9 February 1988. Handley's role was only for three months, but he was able to use the serial's popularity in the United Kingdom to move over there and make public appearances in character.<ref name=\"Roll\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/weekend-gold-coast-bulletin/20190406/283167199932699|title=Neighbours role rolled on and on|date=6 April 2019|work=[[The Gold Coast Bulletin]]|page=68|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref> Handley told a reporter for ''[[The Gold Coast Bulletin]]'', \"I used to put my own ads in the paper with my photo. It used to say ''Neighbours'' star Mark Granger now available for personal appearances'. I put my own phone number, but I used to answer it as my own agent.\"<ref name=\"Roll\"/> Handley's fame also allowed him to star in pantomime.<ref name=\"Roll\"/> In an interview with ''[[New Idea]]'', Handley's co-star, [[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]], whose character [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] is involved with Mark, admitted that the outcome of their storyline was \"a bit of a cliffhanger\".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Annie Steps Out Of Character|last=Ayres|first=Bill|date=28 January 1989|magazine=[[New Idea]]}}</ref>\n\nMark is a rich businessman who meets Jane Harris in the United States. Shortly after she returns to Erinsborough, he arrives to visit her and immediately declares his love for her and buys her some diamond earrings. They go on several dates together and Mark proposes and Jane accepts. They make at the announcement to Jane's friends and neighbours at the [[Robinson family]]'s Christmas party.  Their engagement is met with opposition from Mark's mother, Mrs Granger ([[Mary Ward (actress)|Mary Ward]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/neighbours/a854126/neighbours-who-is-plain-jane-superbrain/|title=Who is Plain Jane Superbrain?|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=6 July 2019|first=Jonathon|last=Hughes}}</ref> who tells Jane she is not suited to her son due to their class differences. Undeterred, Mark is keen to marry Jane and plans are made, but Jane changes her mind after [[Rosemary Daniels]] ([[Joy Chambers]]), who has done business with Mark in the past, tells her that she is making a mistake. Jane hands Mark back the engagement ring and he returns to the United States.\n\n==Others==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Date(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Character\n! scope=\"col\" | Actor\n! scope=\"col\" | Circumstances \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|22\u201326 January}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Elinora Romeo'''}}{{Anchor|Elinora Romeo}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Kate Jason]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 645|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: Penny Fraser|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=22 January 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Tony Romeo (Neighbours)|Tony Romeo]]'s mother. She arrives in Erinsborough when she learns that Tony is getting married. Tony panics and pretends [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] is his fianc\u00e9e and tries to stall Elinora by lying that Jane has chicken pox. Elinora meets Jane for herself and to keep the story going, Jane tells her she was misdiagnosed. More lies occur when Tony tells Elinora his flatmate [[Sally Wells]] is Jane's sister. Elinora quickly works out this is a ruse and discovers the wedding is a lie for Tony to get out of an arranged marriage. She then backs off after realizing Tony must choose his own wife and leaves for Perth.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|11\u201325 February}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Mr Phillips'''}}{{Anchor|Mr Phillips}}\n| {{nowrap|Earl Francis<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 659|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Chris Sheil; Writer: Malcolm Frawley|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=11 February 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Tony Romeo (Neighbours)|Tony Romeo]] and [[Sally Wells]]' landlord. When Sally complains about the condition of the flat, he agrees to have improvements done and mentions there will be a slight rent increase, much to Tony's chagrin. The following week, Phillips visits when [[Helen Daniels]] moves into one of his flats. [[Hilary Robinson]] mentions that there may be a ghost in the flats but Phillips dismisses this and mentions Mary Barrett, the previous tenant, had disappeared without a trace, prompting Hilary to worry. When [[Nell Mangel]] hears something coming from Helen's chimney she too, is convinced there is a spirit and is frightened. Tony discovers that a stray cat named Satan was stuck in the chimney. Phillips returns and thinks that Satan is waiting for Mary to return. He agrees to take the cat home with him and brick up the chimney.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|15 February}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Christine Matthews'''}}{{Anchor|Christine Matthews}}\n| {{nowrap|Helen Milte<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 661|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: David Phillips|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=15 February 1988}}</ref>}}\n| The celebrant who conducts the wedding of [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] and [[Beverly Marshall]] at Number 26 Ramsay Street on Valentine's Day. She also officiates the vow renewal of Jim's son [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul]] and his wife [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail]] shortly after.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|18 February}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Barry Hawkins'''}}{{Anchor|Barry Hawkins}}\n| {{nowrap|James Patrick<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 664|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: John Upton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=18 February 1988}}</ref>}}\n| A used car dealer who shows interest in [[Madge Ramsay]]'s car and cons her into selling for significantly less than the asking price.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|1\u20133 March}} \n| '''Graeme Clifford'''{{Anchor|Graeme Clifford}}\n| {{nowrap|[[John Lee (actor)|John Lee]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 672|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Kendal Flanagan; Writer: Ysabelle Dean|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=1 March 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Graeme arrives in Erinsborough on business from London en route to Brisbane and immediately makes friends with [[Madge Ramsay]]. Madge's fianc\u00e9 [[Harold Bishop]] is jealous. A few days later, Graeme reappears and Madge is stunned to see him back from Brisbane so fast, He explains he never went and remained in Erinsborough all weekend. When Madge thanks him for a letter he supposedly sent, Graeme says he didn't write it. Graeme's wife, June arrives and he explains that he received a telegram from her stating she would be in Erinsborough. The Cliffords then leave for Brisbane, leaving Madge embarrassed.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|16\u201325 March}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Frank Darcy'''}}{{Anchor|Frank Darcy}} \n| {{nowrap|Wyn Roberts<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 683|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: Ian Smith|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=16 March 1988}}</ref>}}\n| An artist friend of [[Helen Daniels]], who arrives in Erinsborough to stay with her ahead of his big art exhibition. Frank is arrested after assaulting a local because he was stressed. Helen pays his bail and he is given a caution. There is an attraction between the two and Frank asks Helen to return to the outback with him, but she declines as she feels she is unable to leave Erinsborough due to her family and friends. Frank leaves alone, but they keep in contact for several years.\n\nIn 2005, in a poll produced by the [[BBC]] asking for the \"20 Most Obscure Neighbours characters\", Frank made the list at Number 13.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/4363958.stm|title=Your 20 favourite obscure Neighbours characters|date=21 October 2005|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|25 March\u20132 May}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Ted Regan'''}}{{Anchor|Ted Regan}}\n| {{nowrap|Julian Branagan<ref name=\"K52\"/>}}\n| A friend of [[#Dave Summers|Dave Summers]]. He and Summers are responsible for running [[Daphne Clarke]] and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] off the road, resulting in Daphne's death. Several Ramsay Street residents tackle them when their car is recognised and the case goes to trial. Summers loses his license for a year and is given a $500 fine while Regan escapes punishment. He goads [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] into hitting him after he tells him that he and Summers framed Mike for assault but Daphne's widower [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] stops any altercation and tells Regan, that his son [[Jamie Clarke (Neighbours)|Jamie]] will grow up without a mother thanks to him and Summers. Regan testifies for the prosecution at Mike's trial and Mike is found guilty of assault.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|7\u201319 April}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Geoff Garrett'''}}{{Anchor|Geoff Garrett}}\n| {{nowrap|Mark Pennell<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 699|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Tony Osicka; Writer: Rick Maier|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=7 April 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Geoff works for [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] and [[Ross Warner (Neighbours)|Ross Warner]]. Ross fires Geoff and he tells Jim's son, [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott]] about Ross' crooked practices and bribery to other companies. Scott does some further investigation and presses Geoff to tell Jim about Ross' dealings, but Geoff folds when Scott and Jim arrive at his house with Ross, and denies everything and drives away.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|13 April 1988,<br>5 September 1989,<br>25 November 1991 \u2013 24 February 1992}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Arthur Bright'''}}{{Anchor|Arthur Bright}}\n| {{nowrap|George Dixon<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 701|series=Neighbours |serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: Lois Booton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=13 April 1988}}</ref>}}<br />{{nowrap|Barry Hill<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 1570|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Alister Smart; Writer: Margot Knight|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=25 November 1991}}</ref>}}\n| A local undertaker who visits [[Nell Mangel]]. She initially mistakes him for a kennel salesman and is horrified when he reveals his occupation. Arthur hires [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] to work for his funeral parlour and is irate when Henry locks a coffin in the hearse ahead of a funeral and promptly fires him. Several years later, Arthur reappears when his teenage daughter [[Phoebe Bright]] begins dating [[Josh Anderson (Neighbours)|Josh Anderson]]. He warns Josh off Phoebe and becomes more and more possessive of his daughter. Josh, undeterred confronts Arthur and Arthur suffers a heart attack and remains in hospital for several weeks. He later dies following surgery.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|22 April 1988 \u2013 29 March 1990}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Gloria Lewis'''}}{{Anchor|Gloria Lewis}}\n| {{nowrap|Beverly Phillips<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 710|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Gary Conway; Writer: Roger Moulton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=22 April 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Gloria meets widower [[Rob Lewis (Neighbours)|Rob Lewis]] and they quickly fall in love and Rob proposes. Their respective children, Dean and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] object but both realise Rob and Gloria are in love and soon give their blessing. Rob and Gloria marry then return to Erinsborough and Gloria begins working as a Barmaid at Rob's local pub, The Waterhole. When Dean graduates from Law School and lands a position with a local law firm, he is worried Gloria and Rob will embarrass him at his graduation party. However, when he realises Gloria knows one of his clients and apologises for his behaviour towards her. Rob is later involved in a car crash and is critically injured and then dies, leaving Gloria devastated. Gloria is later menaced by Sid, the man who sold Rob some stolen car parts and fearing for her own safety, she begins staying with [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] , much to his irritation. After Paul's house is trashed, Gloria agrees to testify against Sid. Gloria makes her last appearance working at the coffee shop, letting customers smuggle in their own alcohol much to the chagrin of [[Harold Bishop]].\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|19 May\u201323 November}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Mrs McCrae'''}}{{Anchor|Mrs McCrae}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Reylene Pearce]]<ref name=\"Nannies\">{{cite episode|title=Episode 728|series=Neighbours |serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Colin Budds; Writer: Ray Harding|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=19 May 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Mrs McCrae applies for the position of nanny to [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]]'s son, [[Jamie Clarke (Neighbours)|Jamie]], but is unsuccessful due to her stern demeanour. She later applies at Lassiter's for the position of housekeeper and remarks that [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] is a little young to be in charge of the complex.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|19\u201320 May}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Carol Barker'''}}{{Anchor|Carol Barker}}\n| {{nowrap|Louise Siversen<ref name=\"Nannies\"/>}}\n| Carol answers [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]]'s advert for a nanny to his son [[Jamie Clarke (Neighbours)|Jamie]]. Carol is a nurse but wants the freedom that the lifestyle of a nanny offers and Des agrees to hire her on the spot. When Jamie cries loudly for his lunch, Carol lets him cry. Des' neighbour [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] is concerned but Carol reassures her everything is fine and refuses to let her see Jamie. When Des arrives home, he notices Jamie is cranky and Gail tells him about Carol. The following day, the same thing happens and Des feeds Jamie himself. Carol then tells Des that Jamie will end up spoiled. Des then promptly tells Carol, to leave which she does.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|24 May 1988,<br>1 November 1993,<br>7 March 1994}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Prue Watkins'''}}{{Anchor|Prue Watkins}}\n| {{nowrap|Lindsay Worthington<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 732|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Kendal Flanagan; Writer: [[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=24 May 1988}}</ref>}}<br />{{nowrap|Jacyl Shaw<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 2036|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Alan Coleman; Directors: Philip East and Grant Fenn; Writer: John Upton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=1 November 1993}}</ref>}}<br />{{nowrap|Olivia Davis<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 2101|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Alan Coleman; Director: Tony Osicka; Writer: Helen MacWhirter|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=7 March 1994}}</ref>}}\n| A receptionist at Lassiter's. Her colleague [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] and [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] set her up on a date with [[David Bishop (Neighbours)|David Bishop]]. David asks Prue out on a second date but she rejects him. Prue reappears sparingly over the next few years.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|2\u201330 June}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Steve Fisher'''}}{{Anchor|Steve Fisher}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Michael Pope (producer)|Michael Pope]] <ref>[[#refkercher|Kercher 1989]], p.53.</ref>}}\n| [[Charlene Robinson]]'s driving instructor, they become friendly while Charlene is in Brisbane visiting her grandparents [[Dan Ramsay|Dan]] and [[Edna Ramsay]]. Charlene's husband [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott]] is jealous, but she reassures him nothing is going on. When Charlene passes her test, she and Steve share a kiss and Charlene is wracked with guilt and confesses to Scott. Charlene's brother [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] warns Steve to keep away, but he is undeterred. Steve then offers Charlene a choice, him or Scott and she chooses her husband. Steve then returns to Brisbane. \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|17 June\u20138 July}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Ian Chadwick'''}}{{Anchor|Ian Chadwick}}\n| {{nowrap|Robin Bowering<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1989-10-06#at-13.30|title=BBC London 6 October 1989 13:30|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]]'s biological father. He reappears when Gail tracks him down and they begin to build up a relationship but Gail's adoptive father, [[Rob Lewis (Neighbours)|Rob Lewis]] is jealous and tries to sabotage Ian's attempts to get to closer to Gail. The final straw comes when Rob breaks a present Ian buys for Gail and her husband [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul]]'s first wedding anniversary and refuses to apologize. Gail is angry at first but Rob calms down and apologizes and gives Ian his blessing to remain in contact with Gail.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|17\u201328 June}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Rachel Frazer'''}}{{Anchor|Rachel Frazer}}\n| {{nowrap|Pamela Hawkesford<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1989-09-25#at-13.30|title=BBC London 25 September 1989 13:30|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| A basketball player who meets [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott Robinson]], [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] and [[Pete Baxter (Neighbours)|Pete Baxter]] when they visit the [[Australian Institute of Sport]]  in [[Canberra]] when Pete is awarded a place there and is assigned Rachel as a mentor. There is an attraction between Mike and Rachel and they begin dating, but Rachel makes it clear basketball is priority. When Pete injures himself and has to see a doctor, he blames Scott but Rachel admits she was the one who informed Pete's trainers about Pete's injury. When the guys leave the institute to return to Erinsborough, Pete thanks Rachel for her all her help. Rachel then tells Mike he needs to get over his ex-girlfriend [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]]. Several weeks later, When Pete disappears from the institute and turns up in Erinsborough and says he could no longer handle it there, Rachel calls Mike to tell him the truth behind Pete's disappearance from the institute, which forces Pete to come clean and admit that he has exacerbated his injury.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| {{nowrap|21\u201322 June}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Carl Banks'''}}{{Anchor|Carl Banks}}\n| {{nowrap|Don Bridges<ref>{{cite web|url=https://donbridges.com/cv/television/|title= Don Bridges CV - Television|publisher=donbridges.com|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}} \n| A kitchen hand at Lassiter's. [[Nell Mangel]] is suspicious of him, despite Carl being highly praised by management. Nell tells [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] that Carl has been stealing from the kitchen. Carl protests his innocence but when Paul opens up a bag, he finds various items of food from the kitchen and Carl is subsequently arrested and charged. However, Carl is released due to lack of a criminal record. He then forces his way into Number 32, blaming Nell for costing him his job and threatens to harm her and make it look like an accident. [[Bronwyn Davies]] arrives home and witnesses the situation and grabs an umbrella and is able to chase Carl out of the house.\n|-\n| {{nowrap|'''Bob Hughes'''}}{{Anchor|Bob Hughes}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Jim Daly (actor)|Jim Daly]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bgmagency.com.au/uploaded/cv/DALY%20Jim.pdf|title=Jim Daly|publisher=BGM Agency|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| Bob is a regular customer at the Waterhole pub who makes sarcastic comments about the new uniforms the bar staff have been told to wear. When Bob begins making drunken lecherous comments to [[Madge Bishop]], her son, [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] pushes Bob and he falls over. Bob then sues for damages. Madge tries to talk him out of it but he is adamant. However, When he gets his medical report back, Bob calls off the suit.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|19 August}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Gary Ling'''}}{{Anchor|Gary Ling}}\n| {{nowrap|Lee Chong}}\n| A Year 8 classmate of [[Todd Landers]]. He enters an ice-cream eating contest at the coffee shop along with Todd and several others, but the event quickly turns into a food fight, resulting in [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] disqualifying all contestants.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|26 August 1988 \u2013 31 January 1989}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Penelope Porter'''}}{{Anchor|Penelope Porter}}\n| {{nowrap|Nikki Wendt}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgmagency.com.au/uploaded/cv/WENDT%20Nicki.pdf|publisher=BGM Agency||title=Nicki Wendt CV}}</ref>\n| A new assistant manager at the Erinsborough branch of the Pacific Bank. She and colleague [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] become very friendly and there is an attraction, but Des is reluctant to take things further as his wife [[Daphne Clarke|Daphne]] has recently died. Dejected, Penny then transfers back to head office. She reappears when Des suffers from an allergy and replaces him at the bank. She admits she has been seeing their boss Gordon Hemmings for a while but after spending the evening with Des, they share a kiss. Des plans to propose after it seems like Penny and Gordon will break up but Penny announces she and Gordon are leaving for Europe, breaking Des' heart.\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|29 August}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Margaret Brownley'''}}{{Anchor|Margaret Brownley}}\n| {{nowrap|Maggie Seren<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 801|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Max Varnel; Writer: Ian Coughlan|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=29 August 1988}}</ref>}}\n| A patient of [[Beverly Marshall]], who suffers an Asthma attack one day in the coffee shop. Beverly acts quickly but Margaret dies en route to hospital. Worse news is to come when the cause of Margaret's death is an overdose as a result of Beverly administering a shot when Margaret had been taking medication orally.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2\u20135 September\n| {{nowrap|'''Brad Fuller'''}}{{Anchor|Brad Fuller}}\n| {{nowrap|Scott Snibson<ref name=\"Unimates\">{{cite episode|title=Episode 805|series=Neighbours |serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Max Varnel; Writer: Lois Booton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=2 September 1988}}</ref>}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| University friends of [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]], who arrive for a study session with Mike at Number 28. While Brad gets along with Mike's girlfriend, [[Bronwyn Davies]], who also works as a live-in nanny, Jackie clashes with Bronwyn by putting down her occupation and making rude comments when she learns Bronwyn did not receive her HSC after dropping out of school to help family on the farm after her mother's death. Several weeks later, at a fete for the local church, Jackie continues putting Bronwyn down and receives a cream pie in the face for her trouble. After Bronwyn refuses to apologize, Jackie storms off.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2 September\u20135 October\n| {{nowrap|'''Jackie Vidor'''}}{{Anchor|Jackie Vidor}}\n| {{nowrap|Shona Ford<ref name=\"Unimates\"/>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|9 September 1988 \u2013 6 June 1989}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Bruce Zadro'''}}{{Anchor|Bruce Zadro}}\n| {{nowrap|Myles Collins<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 810|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Richard Sarrell; Writer: C.V. Schofield|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=9 September 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Nick Page]]'s nemesis at Erinsborough High. He causes trouble at the school dance by making unwanted advances towards Nick's date [[Sharon Davies]] and he and Nick get into a fight, resulting in Nick receiving a black eye ahead of his court date for graffiti. Zadro later frames Nick for tagging principal [[Kenneth Muir (Neighbours)|Kenneth Muir]]'s car, which sees him expelled as a result. Sharon, eager to avenge Nick, concocts a scheme to get Zadro to reveal himself as the truth culprit by pretending to flirt with him and tricks him into confessing over the school tannoy and Nick is reinstated while Zadro is expelled. Nick and Zadro later enter a skateboarding competition where the stipulation is if Zadro wins, he gets a date with Sharon. However, Nick injures himself during practice and [[Matt Robinson (Neighbours)|Matt Williams]] agrees to compete in his place and beats Zadro.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|12 September}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Andrew Brownley'''}}{{Anchor|Andrew Brownley}}\n| {{nowrap|Ian Murton<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bgmagency.com.au/uploaded/cv/MURTON%20Iain.pdf|title=Ian Murton CV|publisher=BGM Agency|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| [[#Margaret Brownley|Margaret Brownley]]'s son. Following Margaret's death, Andrew blames [[Beverly Marshall]], who attended to Margaret and threatens to sue for Malpractice. Beverly's husband, [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] tries to reason with him but Andrew is unrepentant and takes the suit to court. However, Beverly is found not to be at fault.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|20 September 1988 \u2013 17 February 1989}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Vanessa Bailey'''}}{{Anchor|Vanessa Bailey}}\n| {{nowrap|Gretchen Zoland<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 817|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Tony Osicka; Writer: Ray Harding|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=20 September 1988}}</ref>}}\n| A classmate of [[Sharon Davies]] and [[Nick Page]]. She and her friend Pam Muir offer Sharon a cigarette while she is working at the Coffee Shop. Sharon is reluctant but Vanessa and Pam begin taunting her. Sharon takes a puff and dislikes it then throws the cigarette away into a bin, which causes a huge fire. Several months later, Vanessa suggests Nick asks [[#Kenneth Muir|Mr Muir]] if he can paint a mural on a blank wall at the school. However, Nick's plans are cut short when Muir's car is graffitied and he is blamed for it.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|12 October\u20134 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Jessie Ross'''}}{{Anchor|Jessie Ross}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Michelle Kearley]]<ref name=\"Rosses\">{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-02-05#at-13.30|title=Neighbours BBC One London 13:30 5 February 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}} \n| A Year 10 student, who attends a party thrown by classmate [[Sharon Davies]]. She is attracted to [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] who is due to start at his alma mater [[Erinsborough High]] as their teacher. When Jessie arrives with a bruised face to a study session, it causes concern. Mike discovers Jessie's mother [[#Adele Ross|Adele]] is the one hitting her after suspecting her father [[#Ted Ross|Ted]]. When Mike and Jessie have a tutoring session one day after school, their emotions get the best of them and they share a kiss only to be caught by principal  [[Kenneth Muir (Neighbours)|Kenneth Muir]], who angrily suspends Mike. Jessie is then sent to live with her grandparents and tells Mike she loves him before leaving.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|21 October\u20134 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Ted Ross'''}}{{Anchor|Ted Ross}}\n| {{nowrap|Doug Bennett<ref name=\"Rosses\"/>}} \n| The father of [[#Jessie Ross|Jessie Ross]]. Jessie's teacher [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] suspects Ted of beating her when she begins attending school bruised and becomes cagey about the subject of her parents. Mike arrives at the house one day to find that Ted is not the culprit but his wife [[#Adele Ross|Adele]]. After a talk, Mike gives the Rosses a number to call to get some professional help and Ted is grateful. However, after Mike is caught in a compromising position with Jessie, he is livid and makes a threat that Mike will never teach in any other school.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|25\u201326 October}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Adele Ross'''}}{{Anchor|Adele Ross}}\n| {{nowrap|Marian Sinclair<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-02-05|title=Neighbours BBC One London 13:30 2 February 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}  \n| The mother of [[#Jessie Ross|Jessie Ross]]. Jessie's teacher, [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] arrives at their house and learns that Adele is responsible for Jessie's bruises after overhearing shouting. Mike confronts Adele and she threatens to call police if he does not leave but he calls her bluff by saying the police may be interested in learning the full extent of Jessie's bruises. Adele's husband, [[#Ted Ross|Ted]] arrives home and they discuss matters with Mike and after a long discussion, Mike puts the Rosses in touch with a counsellor.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|7\u201317 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Leanne Sterling'''}}{{Anchor|Leanne Sterling}}\n| {{nowrap|[[May Lloyd]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 851|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Julian McSwiney; Writer: Ray Kolle|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=7 November 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Malcolm Clarke (Neighbours)|Malcolm Clarke]]'s girlfriend. There is a big age difference between the two and Malcolm is eager to impress Leanne so he lies that he is wealthy and his son [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des]]' house belongs to him and Des lives there. Malcolm introduces Leanne to his family and leaves her to get acquainted with Des. She begins flirting with Des and making unwanted advances towards him, making him uncomfortable. When she tries to kiss Des and he rejects her, Malcolm walks in and witnesses this and Leanne invents a story that Des made a pass at her after slapping him. Malcolm initially believes Leanne, but Des snaps and urges them to be honest with each other. Leanne then leaves.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|10 November 1988 \u2013 20 February 1990}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Noeline Mangel'''}}{{Anchor|Noeline Mangel}}\n| {{nowrap|Lindy McConchie}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-04-09#at-13.30|title=Schedules: BBC One 9 April 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Joe Mangel]]'s ex-wife. She brings their son [[Toby Mangel|Toby]] to live with Joe while she marries her new partner, Ted Vickers. Noeline returns to collect Toby along with Ted but Toby is reluctant to go as Ted has a temper. When Ted hits Toby for making a mess during dinner, Joe threatens Ted and throws both him and Noeline out. In desperation, Noeline turns to [[#Edith Chubb|Edith Chubb]], who has a grudge against Joe, for help. While Joe is out, Noeline snatches Toby back and returns home only to find Ted does not want Toby living with them and goes to hit her but Joe overpowers him and rescues Toby and Noeline. Toby tries to reunite Joe and Noeline but fails, much to his disappointment. Noeline later receives a job in Darwin and wants Toby to join her, and after some reluctance and some arguing between Joe and Noeline, Toby agrees to live with Noeline and they leave. However, two months later, Noeline is killed in a road accident and Toby returns to Joe.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|30 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Eva Lindstrom'''}}{{Anchor|Eva Lindstrom}}\n| {{nowrap|Lana Darby}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-03-12|title=Schedules: BBC One 12 March 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n| A Scandinavian masseuse who tends to [[Harold Bishop]] when he suffers from a back spasm. She visits him at his home and administers treatment, which is successful.\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last=Hopwood|first=Clive|title=The Official Neighbours Annual 1990|year=1989|publisher=World International|isbn=978-0-7235-6859-9|ref=refhopwood}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wallis|first1=Neil|last2=Hogan|first2=Dave|title=The Neighbours Factfile|year=1989|publisher=[[Angus & Robertson]]|isbn=978-0-207-16382-1|ref=refwallis}}\n* {{cite book|title=Neighbours: The First 10 Years|last=Monroe|first=Josephine|year=1996|publisher=[[Penguin Group]]|isbn=978-0-7181-4212-4|ref=refmonroe|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/neighboursfirst10000monr}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Neighbours Programme Guide|last=Monroe|first=Josephine|year=1994|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|isbn=978-0-86369-831-6|ref=refmonroe2}}\n*{{cite book|title=Neighbours: The Official Annual 1991|last1=McCready|first1=John|last2=Furlong|first2=Nicola|year=1990|publisher=[[Hamlyn (publishers)|Hamlyn]]|isbn=978-0-600-57045-5|ref=refmccready}}\n* {{cite book|title=Neighbours Special|last=Desmond|first=Kesta|year=1990|publisher=Grandreams Limited|isbn=978-0-86227-775-8|ref=refdesmond}}\n* {{cite book|title=Neighbours|last=Kercher|first=John|year=1989|publisher=Grandreams Limited|isbn=978-0-86227-672-0|ref=refkercher}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/characters Characters and cast] at the Official ''Neighbours'' website\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0088580/fullcredits#cast Characters and cast] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n{{Neighbours}}\n{{Neighbours characters|year}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Neighbours characters|1988]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1988|*, Neighbours]]\n[[Category:1988 in Australian television|*, Neighbours]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Neighbours'' characters (1988)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n''[[Neighbours]]'' is an Australian television soap opera that was first broadcast on 18 March 1985. The following is a list of characters that first appeared in the serial in 1988, by order of first appearance. Until February, characters were introduced by the soap's creator and executive producer, [[Reg Watson]]. Thereafter, they were introduced by his successor, [[Don Battye]]. The 4th season of ''Neighbours'' began airing from 13 January 1988. February saw the introduction of Sally Jensen and [[Kristian Schmid]] as siblings [[#Katie Landers|Katie Landers]] and [[#Todd Landers|Todd Landers]]. Comedian [[Greg Fleet]] began portraying criminal [[#Dave Summers|Dave Summers]] in March. [[Tom Oliver]] began playing [[#Lou Carpenter|Lou Carpenter]] in the same month.  [[#David Bishop|David Bishop]] arrived in May, as did [[#Amy Williams|Amy Williams]] and her mother [[#Nene Williams|Nina Williams]]. [[#John Worthington|John Worthington]] was introduced the following month. July saw the arrivals of [[#Bronwyn Davies|Bronwyn Davies]], played by [[Rachel Friend]], her sister [[#Sharon Davies|Sharon Davies]], played by Jessica Muschamp, and Mark Stevens as [[#Nick Page|Nick Page]]. [[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]] began playing [[Joe Mangel]], son of the established [[Nell Mangel]] from August. Irene Inescort arrived as Bronwyn and Sharon's aunt, [[#Edith Chubb|Edith Chubb]] in the same month. September saw the debut of [[#Sylvie Latham|Sylvie Latham]]. [[Mat Stevenson]] took on the role of [[#Skinner|Skinner]] in October, and Joe's son [[#Toby Mangel|Toby Mangel]] made his first appearance in November, as did [[Colin Handley]] as [[#Mark Granger|Mark Granger]].\n\n==Katie Landers==\n{{Main|Katie Landers}}\n'''Katie Landers''' played by Sally Jensen, made her first appearance on 15 February 1988. Jensen and [[Kristian Schmid]], who plays Katie's brother [[Todd Landers]], had not met before or had any acting experience until they attended a drama class with the Actor's Training Studio in Melbourne.<ref name=\"Friends\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Sally+Jensen+and+Neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=news890115_0017_9692|title=Friends and Neighbours|last=Wilson|first=George|date=15 January 1989|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Hopwood9\">[[#refhopwood|Hopwood 1990]], p.9.</ref> Scouts from the Grundy Organisation were also in attendance, on the look out for a pair of actors for ''Neighbours''.<ref name=\"Friends\"/> Jensen and Schmid attended an audition for the roles of regular characters, Katie and Todd, and following a screen test, they were cast.<ref name=\"Friends\"/><ref name=\"Hopwood9\"/> Both actors were at school when they were cast, so they were given an on set tutor and a schoolroom was built behind the studio.<ref name=\"Friends\"/> The BBC said Katie's most notable moment was \"Forcing Joe Mangel to bury a casserole.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_katielanders/page1|title=Character: Katie Landers|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031215121058/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_katielanders%2Fpage1|archivedate=15 December 2003|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' said Katie and Todd's escapades often portrayed storylines which were \"vital themes in the show.\"<ref name=\"Friends\"/>\n{{-}}\n\n==Todd Landers==\n{{Main|Todd Landers}}\n'''Todd Landers''', played by [[Kristian Schmid]], made his first appearance on 15 February 1988. Schmid was 12 years old when he signed himself up for an acting course in Melbourne.<ref name=\"Kid\">{{cite news|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/04/25/12990_gt_features.html|title=That Schmid kid|date=25 April 2008|work=[[Geelong Advertiser]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref> Three weeks later, ''Neighbours'' casting director [[Jan Russ]] came to the school to hold auditions for the show.<ref name=\"Kid\"/> Russ said she was looking for a teenage boy, around 14 or 15, to play the role of Todd Landers.<ref name=\"Kid\"/> Schmid asked to audition and he was cast in the role of Todd.<ref name=\"Kid\"/> Todd was [[Beverly Marshall]]'s (Lisa Armytage) \"cheekily independent nephew\".<ref name=\"Wallis64\">[[#refwallis|Wallis 1989]], p.64.</ref> He and his sister [[Katie Landers]] (Sally Jensen), come to live with Beverly and her husband [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] ([[Alan Dale]]) in [[Ramsay Street]] in order to escape their abusive father.<ref name=\"Wallis64\"/> Schmid remained with ''Neighbours'' until his character was killed off at the age of 17,<ref name=\"Kid\"/> making him the youngest character in the show's history to die.<ref name=\"orange\">{{cite web|title=Neighbours stars: where are they now?|url=http://www.orange.co.uk/entertainment/television/pics/3468_4.htm?linkfrom=entertainment_television_pics_3468_5&link=link_back&article=neighboursstarswherearetheynow|work=[[Orange (telecommunications)|Orange.co.uk]]|publisher=([[France T\u00e9l\u00e9com]])|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref>\nIn 2007, Australian newspaper the ''[[Herald Sun]]'' placed Todd's death at number ten on their list of ''Neighbours'' Top Ten moments.<ref name=\"Moments\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/your-all-time-favourite-moment/story-e6frf99f-1111113933908|title=Your all-time favourite moment|date=11 July 2007|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=Herald and Weekly Times|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Dave Summers==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Dave Summers\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = [[Greg Fleet]]\n| first          = {{start date|1988|3|25|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1988|5|2|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#S|Former; guest]]\n}}\n'''Dave Summers''' played by [[Greg Fleet]], made his first appearance on 25 March 1988. The character was introduced alongside [[#Ted Regan|Ted Regan]] (Julian Branagan) as new villains for the serial.<ref name=\"K52\">[[#refkercher|Kercher 1989]], p.52.</ref> Fleet's character is best known for causing the death of popular character [[Daphne Clarke]] ([[Elaine Smith (actress)|Elaine Smith]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standup.com.au/comedian/greg-fleet|title=Greg Fleet|publisher=The Sit Down Comedy Club|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> When asked about his character's actions, Fleet responded: \"Do I feel bad about killing Daphne on ''Neighbours''? If you are going to be in a show as bad as ''Neighbours'', you should kill one of the main characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thatsmags.com/shanghai/post/24447/greg-fleet|title=Comedian Greg Fleet on His Sociopathic Father Faking His Death|date=1 August 2018|work=That's Magazine|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> In Fleet's biography ''These Things Happen'', he tells of how his role prevented him from having his throat cut in a drug deal gone wrong, as the dealer recognised him from the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/books-magazines/books/these-things-happen-six-shocking-stories-from-greg-fleets-memoir/news-story/e6d6077f9db41c882522a19e1124001c|first=Andrew|last=Bucklow|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=12 October 2018|title=These Things Happen\u2019: Six shocking stories from Greg Fleet's memoir|publisher=[[news.com.au]]}}</ref> Series writer [[Marieke Hardy]] described Fleet's role as \"small but important\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/more-power-to-new-neighbours-20070802-ge5hcc.html|title= More Power to new Neighbours|first=Marieke|last=Hardy|date= 2 August 2007|accessdate=11 July 2019|work= [[The Age]]}}</ref> Prior to playing Summers, Fleet guested as Steve O'Donnel on the serial in 1985.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 50|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Russell Webb; Writer: Craig Wilkins|network=[[Seven Network]]|airdate=24 May 1985}}</ref> \n \nSummers and his friend Ted Regan run Daphne Clarke and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]]'s ([[Fiona Corke]]) car off the road, causing a crash which leaves Gail with amnesia and Daphne in a coma for several weeks. Summers and Regan are caught by [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]]), [[Charlene Robinson]] ([[Kylie Minogue]]), [[Tony Romeo (Neighbours)|Tony Romeo]] ([[Nick Carrafa]]), [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] ([[Alan Dale]]) and [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]) when their car is spotted at Lassiter's by Gail, who recalls the license plate via hypnosis. Daphne dies as a result of her injuries and Summers and Regan are both tried, but Summers only receives a one year suspension of his license and a $500 fine, which enrages [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] ([[Guy Pearce]]). Mike goes after Summers and Regan to fight them, but does not. Summers then reports Mike to the police and he is charged with assault, despite being innocent. Mike is then found guilty of simple assault, but not GBH.\n{{-}}\n\n==Lou Carpenter==\n{{Main|Lou Carpenter}}\n'''Lou Carpenter''', played by [[Tom Oliver]], made his first appearance on 30 March 1988. Oliver appeared for a brief time, having been initially contracted for six months, before leaving and returning in January 1992 as a regular cast member.<ref>{{cite episode|url=|title=This Morning \u2013 Tuesday 25th September|episodelink=|series=This Morning|serieslink=This Morning (TV programme)|credits=Schofield, Phillip; Willoughby, Holly; Oliver, Tom|network=[[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]|airdate=25 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/neighbours/a151395/tom-oliver-lou-carpenter-neighbours/|title=Tom Oliver (Lou Carpenter, 'Neighbours')|first=David|last=Balls|date=7 April 2009|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> He would go on to become one of the longest-serving continuous characters.<ref name=\"OK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ok.co.uk/lifestyle/view/56201/Interview-Tom-Oliver-and-Chris-Milligan/|title=Interview: Tom Oliver and Chris Milligan|date=16 November 2012|work=[[OK!]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> Lou was introduced as an old friend of [[Harold Bishop]] ([[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]) and [[Madge Bishop|Madge Ramsay]] ([[Anne Charleston]]). In their fictional backstory, the characters attended the same school and Lou was Harold's rival for Madge's affections. Oliver said that Lou's feelings for Madge led him to visit Ramsay Street to steal her from Harold on their wedding day.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> Oliver took inspiration for Lou's distinctive \"dirty laugh\" from actor [[Sid James]].<ref name=\"OK\"/> The character also became known for his scams and quick one-liners.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=12\u201325 May 2001|title=Hooked on a feeling|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|issue=179|page=16}}</ref> Oliver received nominations for Funniest Performance at the 2007 and 2008 [[Inside Soap Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/scoop/a64083/inside-soap-awards-2007-the-nominations.html|first=Kris|last=Green|title=Inside Soap Awards 2007: The Nominations|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=3 July 2007|accessdate=4 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://msnuktvsoaps.spaces.live.com/blog/cns!E65397F19A3BDCEA!3110.entry|title=Inside Soap Awards 2008 \u2013 Nominations|date=16 July 2008|publisher=[[MSN TV]]|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==David Bishop==\n{{Main|David Bishop (Neighbours)}}\n'''David Bishop''', played by [[Kevin Harrington (actor)|Kevin Harrington]], made his first appearance during the episode broadcast on 11 May 1988, arriving for his father [[Harold Bishop]]'s ([[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]) wedding.<ref name=\"Miller\"/> Harrington returned to ''Neighbours'' after a 16-year absence in October 2003.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=kevin+harrington+and+neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE030724UUF5V67V1D5|title=Networking|last=Miller|first=Kylie|date=24 July 2003|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=kevin+harrington+and+neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE030515TIIHK0IBD25|title=Networking|last=Miller|first=Kylie|date=15 May 2003|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref> The character, his wife and daughter were written out in 2005, as part of a \"surprise shake-up\" of the cast.<ref name=\"StarsAxed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a21089/three-top-neighbours-stars-axed.html|title=Three top 'Neighbours' stars axed|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|date=8 May 2005|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref> A writer for the [[BBC]]'s ''Neighbours'' website stated that David's most notable moment was \"Getting himself into financial trouble and keeping it a secret.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_davidbishop/page1|title=Character: David Bishop|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=16 July 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040715085004/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_davidbishop%2Fpage1|archivedate=15 July 2004|url-status=live}}</ref> Brian Courtis from ''The Age'' branded David \"Harold's hapless offspring\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=kevin+harrington+and+neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE050509C67KM6APP8T|title=Coming clean while the soap suds swirl|last=Courtis|first=Brian|date=9 May 2005|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Nene Williams==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Nene Williams\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = Leigh Morgan (1988)<br />[[Ally Fowler]] (2016)\n| first          = {{start date|1988|5|25|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|2016|4|12|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]] (1988)<br />[[Jason Herbison]] (2016)\t \n| years          = 1988, 2016\n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#W|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation     = Stewardess<br>Businesswoman<br />Nurse\n| alias          = Nina Williams\n| husband        = Bruce (divorced)\n| daughters      = [[Amy Williams (Neighbours)|Amy Williams]]\n| grandsons      = [[Jimmy Williams (Neighbours)|Jimmy Williams]]\n}}\n'''Nene Williams''' (also '''Nina Williams''') made her first appearance on 25 May 1988. She was originally played by Leigh Morgan. When the character was reintroduced in 2016, [[Ally Fowler]] took over the role. Fowler previously appeared in ''Neighbours'' as [[Zoe Davis]].<ref name=\"JMoran\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/ally-fowler-has-not-been-on-the-set-of-neighbours-for-30-years-but-will-cause-chaos-on-her-return/news-story/4b13d5d166dacca8df23858a8229bc06?nk=cfb429b18655ca0e93ccfee99540e4e4-1456243710|title=Ally Fowler has not been on the set of Neighbours for 30 years but will cause chaos on her return|last=Moran|first=Jonathon|date=23 February 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=12 July 2019}}</ref> She commented, \"It's not difficult to go full circle on ''Neighbours''. The writers are very clever with the way that they can link people together. I love being back with Stefan again, we're having a lot of fun.\"<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> Fowler admitted to some apprehension about joining the cast again, as she likes to move forward, but knowing the role was short term, she thought it would be fun.<ref name=\"SEllis\">{{cite magazine|last=Ellis|first=Sarah|date=26 March \u2013 1 April 2016|title='Kissing Paul Robinson? I was smooching his dad 30 years ago!'|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|issue=12|page=31}}</ref> Fowler began filming in late 2015,<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> and began appearing from 29 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/show-news/ally-fowler-returns-to-neighbours|title=Ally Fowler returns to Neighbours|date=23 February 2016|publisher=[[Tenplay]]|accessdate=12 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160227062905/http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/show-news/ally-fowler-returns-to-neighbours|archivedate=27 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nNene is [[Amy Williams (Neighbours)|Amy Williams]]'s ([[Zoe Cramond]]) mother, and former partner of [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]), who she met while she was an air stewardess.<ref name=\"McLennan\"/> Upon her return, she \"immediately ruffles feathers\" when she sets her sights on one of the married characters,<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> later confirmed to be [[Karl Kennedy]] ([[Alan Fletcher (actor)|Alan Fletcher]]) after he rescues her during a heatwave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/neighbours/a784173/neighbours-spoiler-steph-suffers-a-tragic-relapse-while-at-mediation/|title=Neighbours Spoiler: Steph suffers a tragic relapse while at mediation|first=Daniel|last=Kilkelly|date=20 February 2016|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> [[Network Ten]] drama executive Claire Tonkin called Nene \"complex\" and stated: \"from her first moments on Ramsay Street, this character promises intrigue, secrets and lots of drama\".<ref name=\"JMoran\"/> Of her character's reasons for coming to Erinsborough, Fowler explained that Nene is angry with Paul for not helping her or being a proper father to Amy over the years.<ref name=\"McLennan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/neighbours/neighbours-news/neighbours-ally-fowler-reveals-why-she-cant-keep-away-from-paul-robinson-video-329141/|title=Neighbours' Ally Fowler reveals why she can't keep away from Paul Robinson|last=McLennan|first=Patrick|date=12 April 2016|work=[[What's on TV]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> She said, \"I think there's a desperate need in [Nene] to have family and to experience what having a family would be like and have that support, so in that way she craves Paul's support.\"<ref name=\"McLennan\"/> Fowler also said that Paul would end up using Nene for his own gain.<ref name=\"McLennan\"/>\n\nWhen her grandson [[Jimmy Williams (Neighbours)|Jimmy Williams]] (Darcy Tadich) is injured playing cricket, Nene makes some questionable choices while treating him, leading Amy to ask Karl for a second opinion. Nene feels that Amy does not trust her, and Fowler explained to an ''[[Inside Soap]]'' writer that Nene suffers from anxiety.<ref name=\"Danger\">{{cite magazine|date=12\u201318 March 2016|title=Doug in danger?|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|issue=10|page=31}}</ref> She continued, \"She's had a few problems in the past with her career \u2013 she's got involved with the odd doctor that she shouldn't have, which hasn't ended well \u2013 and she's had to play with the truth a little bit so that Amy doesn't worry.\"<ref name=\"Danger\"/> Knowing that Karl and Amy are watching her, she invents a crisis with [[Doug Willis]] ([[Terence Donovan (actor)|Terence Donovan]]), who she is caring for.<ref name=\"Danger\"/> Nene and Paul later share a kiss, and Nene enjoys playing \"happy families\" with him, Amy and Jimmy. She finds it comforting, but is unaware that Paul has an ulterior motive.<ref name=\"SEllis\"/>\n\nNina organises a [[women in the workplace]] conference at Lassiter's Hotel in [[Erinsborough]], and brings her young daughter Amy with her. She befriends [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] ([[Fiona Corke]]) and invites her to give a talk at the conference when Gail mentions she is married to her boss. Nina is surprised to learn that Gail's husband is Paul Robinson, who she once dated while they worked for the same airline. Gail invites Nina to dinner with her and Paul, but Nina declines the invitation. Paul seeks her out and asks about her life. She explains that she started her own business, fell pregnant with Amy and will be getting married soon. Paul soon works out that Amy is his daughter. Nina tells him that she did not know she was pregnant until after their break up. She also tells him that her fianc\u00e9 Bruce already thinks of Amy as his own and she is leaving that day. Paul asks to be a part of Amy's life, but Nina refuses. Gail tells Nina that Amy might be the only child Paul has. Before she leaves, Nina visits Paul to tells him that she will send him photos of Amy, as well as allowing him to set up a trust fund for Amy's education. Several years later, when Nina and Bruce go through marital problems, Nina sends Amy to live with Paul in Erinsborough for a few months after he visits her in [[New Zealand]].\n\nOver twenty years later, Nina, now calling herself Nene, returns to Erinsborough in the middle of a massive heatwave. She meets her grandson, Jimmy Williams and goes for walk with him, but collapses due to the extreme heat. Karl Kennedy finds Nene and gets her safely to hospital. Amy visits Nene and wants to know what she is doing in town. Nene tells her she has quit her nursing job in Mount Merrion and moved to Erinsborough for a fresh start. Nene develops feelings for Karl, who she assumes is single, but he tells her he is married. Nene is discharged from hospital and stays with Amy and Jimmy at Number 26, along with Amy's boyfriend [[Kyle Canning]] ([[Chris Milligan]]) and his family. Amy asks Karl if there are any nursing jobs available at the hospital and Karl agrees to meet with Nene. Nene discloses that she left her previous job because she had an affair with a doctor who blamed her for a mistake after they split. When the arranged interview falls through, Karl arranges for Nene to be Alzheimer's sufferer Doug Willis' carer.\n\nIn her new position, Nene manipulates situations to spend more time with Karl by lying about Doug's mood swings and calls Karl during a birthday lunch much to the irritation of his wife, [[Susan Kennedy]] ([[Jackie Woodburne]]). She also begins confusing Doug by claiming she is his wife [[Pam Willis]] ([[Sue Jones (actress)|Sue Jones]]), uses Karl's laptop to delete an email from a former colleague, and tracks correspondence between Kyle and his former wife, [[Georgia Brooks]] ([[Saskia Hampele]]). However, Doug is able to see through her act and tells the Kennedys, who confront Nene about her erratic behaviour. Nene admits that she has not been taking her anti-depressant medication. Doug agrees not to report Nene, as he knows what it is like to lose control of his own mind. Following this, Nene turns to Paul for support and falls for him again. When she tries to kiss him, Paul rebuffs Nene and lets her down gently. When an explosion occurs at Lassiter's hotel, Nene puts on a nurse's uniform and attempts to treat a comatose [[Jack Callahan (Neighbours)|Jack Callaghan]] ([[Andrew Morley]]), but Doug's granddaughter, [[Paige Smith]] ([[Olympia Valance]]) recognises her and she flees. When Paul is accused of causing the explosion, he asks Nene to provide an alibi for him and she does so, but retracts it when she sees Paul kissing [[Terese Willis]] ([[Rebekah Elmaloglou]]). She then leaves Erinsborough to stay in a retreat in the Blue Mountains and receives treatment for her condition.\n\n==Amy Williams==\n{{Main|Amy Williams (Neighbours)}}\n'''Amy Williams''' (previously '''Robinson''') made her first appearance on 25 May 1988. She was originally played by Nicolette Minster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/review-louise-joy-mccrae-nicolette-minster-in-girls-uninterrupted/story-fncv4qxa-1226314838646|title=Review: Louise Joy McCrae, Nicolette Minister in Girls Uninterrupted|first=Matthew|last=Schultz|date=30 March 2012|accessdate=10 August 2014|work=[[Herald Sun]]}}</ref> Minster was around three years old when she was cast in the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/mediaflash/docs/ob_28aug13_az/4|title=On target for more laughs|last=Richardson|first=Mark|date=28 August 2013|work=The Melbourne Observer via [[Issuu]]|page=4|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> Amy was introduced to ''Neighbours'' as the first child of established character [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]).<ref>[[#refmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.16.</ref> When the character returned to the show in 1992, Sheridan Compagnino took over the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_amyrobinson/page1|title=Character: Amy Robinson|publisher=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=14 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050409050618/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_amyrobinson%2Fpage1|archivedate=9 April 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> Amy was reintroduced to ''Neighbours'' with actress [[Zoe Cramond]] taking over the role in 2015.<ref name=\"AllChange\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s14/neighbours/news/a647877/all-change-for-neighbours-four-new-regulars-join-the-soaps-cast.html#~pcYKylGLFjEg03|title=All change for Neighbours: Four new regulars join the soap's cast|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=17 May 2015|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> Cramond described Amy as \"very straightforward yet quite complex\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenplay.com.au/channel-eleven/neighbours/features/zoe-cramond-joins-neighbours|title=Zoe Cramond joins Neighbours|date=4 June 2015|publisher=[[Network Ten]]|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> A ''Soap World'' contributor branded her \"mysteriously sexy and tomboyish\".<ref>{{cite magazine|date=July 2015|title=Come to grandpa!|magazine=Soap World|issue=270|page=19}}</ref>\n\n==John Worthington==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name = John Worthington\n| series = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer = [[Brian James (actor)|Brian James]]\n| first = {{start date|1988|6|9|df=y}}\n| last = {{end date|1988|10|24|df=y}}\n| introducer = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#W|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation = Retired dentist\n| wife = Iris Worthington (until 1987)<br />[[Nell Mangel]] (1988\u2013; his death)\n| daughters = Caroline Worthington\n}}\n'''John Worthington''', played by [[Brian James (actor)|Brian James]], made his first appearance on 9 June 1988.<ref name=\"Devlyn\">{{cite journal|last=Devlyn|first=Darren|date=15 October 1988|title=Nell bowls up to the altar|journal=[[TV Week]]|pages=8\u20139}}</ref> The character was introduced as a love interest for [[Nell Mangel]] ([[Vivean Gray]]). He and Nell become bowling colleagues and share \"a strong and mutual need for love and companionship.\"<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/> The couple soon become engaged. Shortly before the wedding, Nell has second thoughts, while John needs reassurance from [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] ([[Paul Keane]]) and [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]).<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/> James commented, \"He does have a few anxious moments before Nell arrives.\"<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/> Nell and John became the third couple to marry in 1988.<ref name=\"Devlyn\"/>\n\nJohn is a widowed, retired dentist. He meets Nell Mangel when she joins the local bowls team. There is an attraction between them, but their relationship breaks down when John tires of Nell's gossipy ways. However, John reappears several months later and they get reacquainted. Nell's son, [[Joe Mangel]] ([[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]]) takes a dislike to John and throws him out of the house. Joe later warms to John and gives him his blessing to marry Nell. When a 30-year-old letter written by John's late wife Iris reveals his infidelity, Nell breaks off the engagement. But she eventually realises John's affair was a long time ago and the wedding goes ahead. John and Nell bid farewell to all their friends in Erinsborough and relocate to [[St. Albans]]. When Nell's granddaughter, [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]])  returns to Erinsborough in 2018, she mentions that John has since died.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Bronwyn Davies==\n{{Main|Bronwyn Davies}}\n'''Bronwyn Davies''' played by [[Rachel Friend]]. She made her first appearance on 7 July 1988. Following [[Kylie Minogue]]'s ([[Charlene Robinson]]) departure, the ''Neighbours'' producers were about to begin a nation-wide search for a new female actress to join the show, when they discovered Friend.<ref name=\"NewNeighbour\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rachel+Friend+and+Neighbours&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=news880625_0183_0393|title=Your New Neighbour|date=25 June 1988|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|page=51|accessdate=6 June 2011}}</ref> Friend chose to postpone her university degree to join ''Neighbours'' as country girl, Bronwyn Davies.<ref name=\"NewNeighbour\"/> In 1990, Friend decided to quit the serial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/TV--Radio/Role-of-honour/2005/03/13/1110649050747.html|title=Role of honour|last=Idato|first=Michael|date=14 March 2005|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=14 September 2010}}</ref> For her portrayal of Bronwyn, Friend won \"Most Popular Actress\" at the 1990 [[Logie Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1990 TV Week Logie Awards|url=http://tvweek.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=732945&showcomments=true|work=[[TV Week]]|publisher=[[Ninemsn]]|accessdate=13 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324005436/http://tvweek.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=732945&showcomments=true|archive-date=24 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> During a feature on past ''Neighbours'' characters, telecommunications network [[Orange (telecommunications)|Orange]], described Bronwyn's most memorable moment as: \"Accidentally pushing good pal Henry Ramsay (played by Craig McLachlan) down some steps. Believing the mulleted larrikin was unconscious, Bronwyn rushed to his side and professed her undying love for him \u2013 whereupon Henry opened his eyes and admitted he felt the same. Aaah!\"<ref name=\"orange\"/>\n\n==Nick Page==\n{{Main|Nick Page}}\n'''Nick Page''', played by Mark Stevens, made his first appearance on 22 July 1988. Stevens joined the cast of ''Neighbours'' soon after taking part in ''[[Young Talent Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=Tony|title=What a soap buster|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&kw=mark+stevens&pb=all_ffx&dt=enterRange&dr=1month&sd=01%2F01%2F1987&ed=01%2F01%2F1996&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=adv&clsPage=1&docID=news890702_0157_1723|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=([[Fairfax Media]])|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=2 July 1989}}</ref> Stevens' first scene consisted of Nick trying to find his stolen [[Walkman]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Neighbours the whole story|magazine=[[Fast Forward (magazine)|Fast Forward]]|date=1-7 August 1990|issue=47|publisher=[[BBC Magazines]]}}</ref> Josephine Monroe, author of ''Neighbours: the first 10 years'' described Nick as one [[Helen Daniels]]' ([[Anne Haddy]]) many waifs and strays, a budding artist and having a recalcitrant personality.<ref>[[#refmmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.42.</ref><ref>[[#refmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.98.</ref> The BBC described Nick's most notable moment as being \"his first appearance when he was caught spraying graffiti\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_nickpage/page1|title=Character: Nick Page|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=23 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The episode featuring Nick rescuing Todd and Katie from Skinner was watched by 21 million viewers in the United Kingdom. It was the most watched episode of any show during 1990.<ref>{{cite web|title=BARB Since 1981|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/facts/since1981?year=1990&view=top10|work=barb.co.uk|publisher=([[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]])|accessdate=23 February 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622023437/http://www.barb.co.uk/facts/since1981?year=1990&view=top10|archivedate=22 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Sharon Davies==\n{{Main|Sharon Davies}}\n'''Sharon Davies''', played by Jessica Muschamp, made her first appearance on 29 July 1988. Muschamp landed the role while completing her [[Victorian Certificate of Education|VCE]] in 1988.<ref name=\"TheAge\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/arts/2010/02/27/1266687178528.html?page=2|title=That was then, this is now \u2013 Jessica Muschamp|date=28 February 2010|work=The Age |location=Australia|publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref> Muschamp said she thought the audition would be a good experience and that she did not expect to get the role.<ref name=\"Hopwood47\">[[#refhopwood|Hopwood 1990]], p.47.</ref> During her time with ''Neighbours'', Muschamp said she \"had a ball\" working with the other members of the cast.<ref name=\"TheAge\"/> Sharon is described as a \"impetuous, laid back character.\"<ref name=\"Special\">{{Cite book|last=Hopwood|first=Clive|title=Neighbours Special|year=1990|publisher=World International Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-0-7235-6895-7|page=16}}</ref> She is bubbly, but tactless. Sharon often insults people, but she does not mean to and she can be a little thoughtless.<ref name=\"Special\"/> In 1990, during a cast exodus, producers decided to send the character to New Zealand.<ref name=\"TheAge\"/> In ''Neighbours: The Official Annual 1991'', authors John McCready and Nicola Furlong said Muschamp had made her mark on ''Neighbours''. They added \"The love lives of those such as Nick Page and Sharon Davies have made the programme perhaps the most popular viewing for teenagers around the world.\"<ref>[[#refmccready|McCready 1990]], p.19, 59.</ref>\n\n==Joe Mangel==\n{{Main|Joe Mangel}}\n'''Joe Mangel''', played by [[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]], made his first appearance on 8 August 1988.<ref name=\"Identity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/mark-little2/accidental-fame-of-an-anarchist_b_6807628.html|title=Mangel'd: The Accidental Fame of an Anarchist Or How an Aussie Soap Character Stole my Identity|last=Little|first=Mark|date=5 March 2015|work=[[The Huffington Post|The Huffington Post UK]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> Little was initially contracted for 13 weeks,<ref name=\"MakingMark\">{{cite magazine|last=Devlyn|first=Darren|date=6 August 1988|title=Making his Mark|magazine=[[TV Week]]|page=25}}</ref> but this was soon extended.<ref name=\"Identity\"/> Joe is the estranged son of [[Nell Mangel]] ([[Vivean Gray]]).<ref name=\"MakingMark\"/> Very little was known about Joe prior to his introduction, and Darren Devlyn branded him \"an unknown quantity in Erinsborough\".<ref name=\"MakingMark\"/> Joe is nothing like his mother, and he was described as being an \"unreconstructed oaf who likes drinking beer\", green fingered and brutish. Nell and [[Dorothy Burke]] ([[Maggie Dence]]) attempt to make Joe change his ways, and he often clashes with his niece [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]]).<ref>[[#refmonroe|Monroe 1996]], p.79\u201380.</ref> Little chose to leave the serial in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal|title=It's time to move on|journal=[[TV Week]]|date=4\u201310 May 1991}}</ref> Lorna Cooper, editor of [[MSN|MSN TV]], branded Joe one of show's legendary characters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tv.uk.msn.com/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=149729015&page=35|title=TV's Neighbours: where are they now?|publisher=[[MSN]]|author=Cooper, Lorna|date=17 March 2010|accessdate=14 July 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vwX2EQK1?url=http://tv.uk.msn.com/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=149729015&page=35|archivedate=23 January 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> While the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'s'' Polly Hudson chose Joe as one of her favourite characters, citing his \"funny, sweet and ute-obsessed\" personality and comedy moments as her reasons why.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/08/03/vote-for-your-favourite-soap-star-in-the-new-mirror-soap-awards-115875-21566830/|title=Vote for your favourite soap star in the new Mirror Soap Awards|last=Hudson|first=Polly|date=3 August 2009|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=14 July 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vwWyyyFG?url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2009/08/03/vote-for-your-favourite-soap-star-in-the-new-mirror-soap-awards-115875-21566830/|archivedate=23 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Edith Chubb==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Edith Chubb\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = Irene Inescort\n| first          = {{start date|1988|8|10|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1989|2|24|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| years          = 1988\u20131989\n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#C|Former; recurring]]\n| brothers       = Gordon Davies\n| nieces         = [[Bronwyn Davies]]<br />[[Sharon Davies]]\n| nephews        = Bill Davies\n}}\n'''Edith \"Edie\" Chubb''', played by Irene Inescort, made her first appearance on 10 August 1988 and departed on 24 February 1989. Edie is the aunt of [[Bronwyn Davies]] ([[Rachel Friend]]) and [[Sharon Davies]] (Jessica Muschamp).<ref>[[#refmonroe2|Monroe 1994]], p.209.</ref> She purchases [[Ramsay Street#No. 30|Number 30 Ramsay Street]] and moves in with her nieces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shortlist.com/news/neighbours-ramsay-street-house-up-for-sale|title=Neighbours' Ramsay Street house up for sale|work=[[Shortlist]]|date=24 January 2013|accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref> [[Grace Dent]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented that Edie had an echo of ''[[Coronation Street]]'s'' [[Ena Sharples]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/jul/30/tvandradio.theguide|first=Grace|last=Dent|title=Crowned with Glory|date=30 July 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nEdie arrives in Erinsborough in the middle of a Murder Mystery party her nieces Bronwyn and Sharon are attending. She tries to take Sharon back to [[Narrabri]], but she refuses to leave, so Edie allows the girls to stay with [[Nell Mangel]] ([[Vivean Gray]]). Sharon learns Edie is planning to buy Number 30 and that she has asked [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] (Paul Keane) to be a proxy bidder for her. Sharon tries to derail the auction by disguising herself as an elderly woman and attempting to drive the price up. Sharon succeeds, but Des quickly sees through the ruse and Sharon's bid is voided, and Edie buys the house. When Edie returns several weeks later, she is unimpressed to find Bronwyn and Sharon kissing their respective boyfriends [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] ([[Guy Pearce]]) and [[Nick Page]] (Mark Stevens). Edie then moves the girls in with her and tries to control their lives, but Sharon manages to manipulate Edie into letting her see Nick when she gets stuck in a tree attempting to rescue her cat, Arthur.\n\nEdie is less than pleased when Bronwyn begins dating [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] ([[Craig McLachlan]]), but is delighted when they break up, however, she is horrified when they reconcile. Edie also embarks on a feud with neighbour [[Joe Mangel]] ([[Mark Little (Australian actor)|Mark Little]]). This culminates in Joe playing a practical joke by sending a [[marijuana]] plant to Number 30, resulting in Edie's arrest. Bent on revenge, Edie assists Joe's ex-wife [[#Noeline Mangel|Noeline Mangel]] (Lindy McConchie) in snatching their son [[Toby Mangel]] (Finn Greentree-Keane) from Joe, who he is currently staying with. This move endangers Toby as his violent stepfather, Ted Vickers (John Jacobs) attacks him and Noeline, but Joe saves them in the nick of time. Edie apologises to Joe as she had no idea of Ted's violent nature. Soon after, she leaves Erinsborough to look after a sick relative.\n{{-}}\n\n==Sylvie Latham==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| name           = Sylvie Latham\n| portrayer      = Christine Harris\n| first          = {{start date|1988|9|22|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1988|9|27|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#S|Former; guest]]\n| occupation     = Model\n}}\n'''Sylvie Latham''', played by Christine Harris, made her first appearance on 22 September 1988. Kesta Desmond author of ''Neighbours Special'', commented that Sylvie made a dramatic entrance to the show, as within one episode she had decided to \"romantically tackle\" [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott Robinson]] ([[Jason Donovan]]).<ref name=\"D33\">[[#refdesmond|Desmond 1990]], p.33.</ref> Desmond said Sylvie's method of seduction was \"far from subtle!\"<ref name=\"D33\"/> Of her role, Desmond stated: \"It caused quite a stir filming those scenes, but it was a lot of fun.\"<ref name=\"D33\"/> She thought she would get \"a lot of flack\" from fans of Scott, but she was surprised when she did not receive many complaints.<ref name=\"D33\"/>\n\nSylvie is a model who works for the same agency as [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] ([[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]]). Scott Robinson interviews Sylvie at Jane's suggestion for his article for the ''Erinsborough News''. Sylvie and Scott have lunch and she is clearly attracted to him. When Sylvie admits that she is attracted to Scott, Jane warns her off and tells her that Scott is married to her friend [[Charlene Robinson]] ([[Kylie Minogue]]), who is currently in [[Brisbane]]. Undeterred, Sylvie steps up her quest to seduce Scott, who rebuffs her advances. Angry with being rejected, Sylvie lies to Jane that Scott spent the night with her at Lassiter's. Scott denies this and he and Jane confront Sylvie, who admits that she did it for attention because she felt like  she always had to live in her sister's shadow. She apologises to Scott.\n\n==Skinner==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Skinner\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = [[Mat Stevenson]]\n| first          = {{start date|1988|10|31|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1989|4|19|df=y}}\n| introducer      = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| years           = 1988\u20131989\n| classification  = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#S|Former; recurring]]\n}}\n'''Skinner''', played by [[Mat Stevenson]] made his first appearance on 31 October and departed on 19 April 1989.\nIn a 2005 interview with the BBC celebrating 20 years of Neighbours, Stevenson opined that serial's success was due to its cheerfulness \"There's a fair amount of optimism, youthful exuberance and the sunshine that just appeals.\" <ref name=\"Decades\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4358995.stm|title=Two decades with the Neighbours|first=Phill|last=Mercer|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> He added \"It is 15 years since I've been on the show but I still get recognised as Skinner. Last year I was travelling on a train in Melbourne and I signed 40 autographs. It's amazing how revered I am in other walks of life. Being in Neighbours has done me nothing but favours.\"<ref name= \"Decades\"/>\n\nSkinner meets [[Todd Landers]] ([[Kristian Schmid]]) at a local arcade when he runs away from home. When [[Helen Daniels]] ([[Anne Haddy]]) and [[Nick Page]] (Mark Stevens) come looking for Todd, Skinner lies and tells them he saw him at another arcade. He then invites Todd back to his squat and teaches him how to \"survive\" on the streets by stealing. Skinner gives Todd an ultimatum; either earn his keep or go back onto the streets. Todd reluctantly complies with Skinner's plan to rob a carphone warehouse. They go to a warehouse but when they spot Helen and Nick they run off. On the night of the robbery, Nick catches up with Skinner and Todd and fights with Skinner but is arrested when the alarm is triggered and Skinner gets away. Skinner warns Todd not to say anything. Feeling guilty, Todd flees while Skinner is asleep and returns home in order to exonerate Nick.\n\nSkinner turns up on Ramsay Street and plans to rob Number 22, forcing Todd to be his accomplice but Todd's sister, [[Katie Landers|Katie]] (Sally Jensen) catches him in the act and he threatens her. Fearful for his sister's safety, Todd unhooks [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul]] ([[Stefan Dennis]]) and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]]'s ([[Fiona Corke]]) VCR. Gail arrives home unexpectedly and rescues Katie and Todd chases after Skinner. A passing Nick helps overpower Skinner and he is arrested. Several months later, Skinner reappears when Nick and his girlfriend [[Sharon Davies]] (Jessica Muschamp) hitch a lift back to Erinsborough after running away. He drives off with Sharon causing her to panic but offers to take her back to Erinsborough and she thanks him with a kiss. Skinner and Sharon begin dating much to Nick's horror and everyone tries to warn Sharon about Skinner but she will not listen. The final straw comes when Skinner menaces Sharon's older sister, [[Bronwyn Davies|Bronwyn]] ([[Rachel Friend]]) and attempts to force himself on her but Sharon catches him in the act. Skinner is then arrested once again.\n{{-}}\n\n==Toby Mangel==\n{{Main|Toby Mangel}}\n'''Toby Mangel''' made his first appearance on 10 November 1988. He was originally played by Finn Greentree-Keane until 1990.<ref name=\"Where\">{{cite magazine|date=8\u201321 December 2001|title=Where are they now? - Ben Geurens|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|publisher=Attic Futura (UK) Ltd|issue=194|page=71}}</ref> Ben Geurens then took over the role when Greentree-Keane decided to leave.<ref name=\"Where\"/> Geurens had previously done a stunt on ''Neighbours'' the year before with the New Generation Stunts company and had doubled for some of the other children.<ref name=\"Where\"/> When the producers needed a new actor to play the part of Toby they thought Geurens would be ideal as he already had experience with the show.<ref name=\"Where\"/> Guerens remained in the serial until 1993.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Home+truths.-a0137900710|title=Home truths|last=Whitfield|first=Graeme|date=25 October 2005|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref> A writer for the BBC said Toby's most notable moment was \"coping with his mother and Kerry's deaths\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content/_tobymangel/page1|title=Character: Toby Mangel|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=1 April 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050413194314/http://www.bbc.co.uk/neighbours/whoswho/characterbiogs/index.shtml?content%2F_tobymangel%2Fpage1|archivedate=13 April 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> A columnist for ''Inside Soap'' called Toby \"the cutest child on Ramsay Street\" and said he became a favourite with viewers.<ref name=\"Where\"/> \n{{-}}\n\n==Mark Granger==\n{{Infobox soap character\t \n| name           = Mark Granger\n| series         = Neighbours\t \n| portrayer      = [[Colin Handley]]\n| first          = {{start date|1988|11|23|df=y}}\n| last           = {{end date|1989|2|9|df=y}}\n| introducer     = [[Don Battye]]\t \n| classification = [[Recurring characters of Neighbours#G|Former;recurring]]\n| father         = Mark Granger\n| mother         = Mrs Granger\n| grandfathers    = Mark Granger\n| years          = 1988\u20131989\n| occupation     = Businessman\n\n}}\n'''Mark Granger''' played by [[Colin Handley]], made his first appearance on 23 November 1988 and departed on 9 February 1988. Handley's role was only for three months, but he was able to use the serial's popularity in the United Kingdom to move over there and make public appearances in character.<ref name=\"Roll\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/weekend-gold-coast-bulletin/20190406/283167199932699|title=Neighbours role rolled on and on|date=6 April 2019|work=[[The Gold Coast Bulletin]]|page=68|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref> Handley told a reporter for ''[[The Gold Coast Bulletin]]'', \"I used to put my own ads in the paper with my photo. It used to say ''Neighbours'' star Mark Granger now available for personal appearances'. I put my own phone number, but I used to answer it as my own agent.\"<ref name=\"Roll\"/> Handley's fame also allowed him to star in pantomime.<ref name=\"Roll\"/> In an interview with ''[[New Idea]]'', Handley's co-star, [[Annie Jones (actress)|Annie Jones]], whose character [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] is involved with Mark, admitted that the outcome of their storyline was \"a bit of a cliffhanger\".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Annie Steps Out Of Character|last=Ayres|first=Bill|date=28 January 1989|magazine=[[New Idea]]}}</ref>\n\nMark is a rich businessman who meets Jane Harris in the United States. Shortly after she returns to Erinsborough, he arrives to visit her and immediately declares his love for her and buys her some diamond earrings. They go on several dates together and Mark proposes and Jane accepts. They make at the announcement to Jane's friends and neighbours at the [[Robinson family]]'s Christmas party.  Their engagement is met with opposition from Mark's mother, Mrs Granger ([[Mary Ward (actress)|Mary Ward]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/neighbours/a854126/neighbours-who-is-plain-jane-superbrain/|title=Who is Plain Jane Superbrain?|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=6 July 2019|first=Jonathon|last=Hughes}}</ref> who tells Jane she is not suited to her son due to their class differences. Undeterred, Mark is keen to marry Jane and plans are made, but Jane changes her mind after [[Rosemary Daniels]] ([[Joy Chambers]]), who has done business with Mark in the past, tells her that she is making a mistake. Jane hands Mark back the engagement ring and he returns to the United States.\n\n==Others==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Date(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Character\n! scope=\"col\" | Actor\n! scope=\"col\" | Circumstances \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|22\u201326 January}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Elinora Romeo'''}}{{Anchor|Elinora Romeo}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Kate Jason]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 645|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: Penny Fraser|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=22 January 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Tony Romeo (Neighbours)|Tony Romeo]]'s mother. She arrives in Erinsborough when she learns that Tony is getting married. Tony panics and pretends [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] is his fianc\u00e9e and tries to stall Elinora by lying that Jane has chicken pox. Elinora meets Jane for herself and to keep the story going, Jane tells her she was misdiagnosed. More lies occur when Tony tells Elinora his flatmate [[Sally Wells]] is Jane's sister. Elinora quickly works out this is a ruse and discovers the wedding is a lie for Tony to get out of an arranged marriage. She then backs off after realizing Tony must choose his own wife and leaves for Perth.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|11\u201325 February}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Mr Phillips'''}}{{Anchor|Mr Phillips}}\n| {{nowrap|Earl Francis<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 659|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Chris Sheil; Writer: Malcolm Frawley|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=11 February 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Tony Romeo (Neighbours)|Tony Romeo]] and [[Sally Wells]]' landlord. When Sally complains about the condition of the flat, he agrees to have improvements done and mentions there will be a slight rent increase, much to Tony's chagrin. The following week, Phillips visits when [[Helen Daniels]] moves into one of his flats. [[Hilary Robinson]] mentions that there may be a ghost in the flats but Phillips dismisses this and mentions Mary Barrett, the previous tenant, had disappeared without a trace, prompting Hilary to worry. When [[Nell Mangel]] hears something coming from Helen's chimney she too, is convinced there is a spirit and is frightened. Tony discovers that a stray cat named Satan was stuck in the chimney. Phillips returns and thinks that Satan is waiting for Mary to return. He agrees to take the cat home with him and brick up the chimney.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|15 February}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Christine Matthews'''}}{{Anchor|Christine Matthews}}\n| {{nowrap|Helen Milte<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 661|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: David Phillips|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=15 February 1988}}</ref>}}\n| The celebrant who conducts the wedding of [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] and [[Beverly Marshall]] at Number 26 Ramsay Street on Valentine's Day. She also officiates the vow renewal of Jim's son [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul]] and his wife [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail]] shortly after.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|18 February}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Barry Hawkins'''}}{{Anchor|Barry Hawkins}}\n| {{nowrap|James Patrick<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 664|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: John Upton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=18 February 1988}}</ref>}}\n| A used car dealer who shows interest in [[Madge Ramsay]]'s car and cons her into selling for significantly less than the asking price.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|1\u20133 March}} \n| '''Graeme Clifford'''{{Anchor|Graeme Clifford}}\n| {{nowrap|[[John Lee (actor)|John Lee]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 672|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Reg Watson; Director: Kendal Flanagan; Writer: Ysabelle Dean|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=1 March 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Graeme arrives in Erinsborough on business from London en route to Brisbane and immediately makes friends with [[Madge Ramsay]]. Madge's fianc\u00e9 [[Harold Bishop]] is jealous. A few days later, Graeme reappears and Madge is stunned to see him back from Brisbane so fast, He explains he never went and remained in Erinsborough all weekend. When Madge thanks him for a letter he supposedly sent, Graeme says he didn't write it. Graeme's wife, June arrives and he explains that he received a telegram from her stating she would be in Erinsborough. The Cliffords then leave for Brisbane, leaving Madge embarrassed.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|16\u201325 March}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Frank Darcy'''}}{{Anchor|Frank Darcy}} \n| {{nowrap|Wyn Roberts<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 683|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: Ian Smith|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=16 March 1988}}</ref>}}\n| An artist friend of [[Helen Daniels]], who arrives in Erinsborough to stay with her ahead of his big art exhibition. Frank is arrested after assaulting a local because he was stressed. Helen pays his bail and he is given a caution. There is an attraction between the two and Frank asks Helen to return to the outback with him, but she declines as she feels she is unable to leave Erinsborough due to her family and friends. Frank leaves alone, but they keep in contact for several years.\n\nIn 2005, in a poll produced by the [[BBC]] asking for the \"20 Most Obscure Neighbours characters\", Frank made the list at Number 13.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/4363958.stm|title=Your 20 favourite obscure Neighbours characters|date=21 October 2005|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|25 March\u20132 May}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Ted Regan'''}}{{Anchor|Ted Regan}}\n| {{nowrap|Julian Branagan<ref name=\"K52\"/>}}\n| A friend of [[#Dave Summers|Dave Summers]]. He and Summers are responsible for running [[Daphne Clarke]] and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] off the road, resulting in Daphne's death. Several Ramsay Street residents tackle them when their car is recognised and the case goes to trial. Summers loses his license for a year and is given a $500 fine while Regan escapes punishment. He goads [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] into hitting him after he tells him that he and Summers framed Mike for assault but Daphne's widower [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] stops any altercation and tells Regan, that his son [[Jamie Clarke (Neighbours)|Jamie]] will grow up without a mother thanks to him and Summers. Regan testifies for the prosecution at Mike's trial and Mike is found guilty of assault.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|7\u201319 April}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Geoff Garrett'''}}{{Anchor|Geoff Garrett}}\n| {{nowrap|Mark Pennell<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 699|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Tony Osicka; Writer: Rick Maier|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=7 April 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Geoff works for [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] and [[Ross Warner (Neighbours)|Ross Warner]]. Ross fires Geoff and he tells Jim's son, [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott]] about Ross' crooked practices and bribery to other companies. Scott does some further investigation and presses Geoff to tell Jim about Ross' dealings, but Geoff folds when Scott and Jim arrive at his house with Ross, and denies everything and drives away.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|13 April 1988,<br>5 September 1989,<br>25 November 1991 \u2013 24 February 1992}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Arthur Bright'''}}{{Anchor|Arthur Bright}}\n| {{nowrap|George Dixon<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 701|series=Neighbours |serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Steve Mann; Writer: Lois Booton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=13 April 1988}}</ref>}}<br />{{nowrap|Barry Hill<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 1570|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Alister Smart; Writer: Margot Knight|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=25 November 1991}}</ref>}}\n| A local undertaker who visits [[Nell Mangel]]. She initially mistakes him for a kennel salesman and is horrified when he reveals his occupation. Arthur hires [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] to work for his funeral parlour and is irate when Henry locks a coffin in the hearse ahead of a funeral and promptly fires him. Several years later, Arthur reappears when his teenage daughter [[Phoebe Bright]] begins dating [[Josh Anderson (Neighbours)|Josh Anderson]]. He warns Josh off Phoebe and becomes more and more possessive of his daughter. Josh, undeterred confronts Arthur and Arthur suffers a heart attack and remains in hospital for several weeks. He later dies following surgery.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|22 April 1988 \u2013 29 March 1990}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Gloria Lewis'''}}{{Anchor|Gloria Lewis}}\n| {{nowrap|Beverly Phillips<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 710|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Gary Conway; Writer: Roger Moulton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=22 April 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Gloria meets widower [[Rob Lewis (Neighbours)|Rob Lewis]] and they quickly fall in love and Rob proposes. Their respective children, Dean and [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] object but both realise Rob and Gloria are in love and soon give their blessing. Rob and Gloria marry then return to Erinsborough and Gloria begins working as a Barmaid at Rob's local pub, The Waterhole. When Dean graduates from Law School and lands a position with a local law firm, he is worried Gloria and Rob will embarrass him at his graduation party. However, when he realises Gloria knows one of his clients and apologises for his behaviour towards her. Rob is later involved in a car crash and is critically injured and then dies, leaving Gloria devastated. Gloria is later menaced by Sid, the man who sold Rob some stolen car parts and fearing for her own safety, she begins staying with [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] , much to his irritation. After Paul's house is trashed, Gloria agrees to testify against Sid. Gloria makes her last appearance working at the coffee shop, letting customers smuggle in their own alcohol much to the chagrin of [[Harold Bishop]].\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|19 May\u201323 November}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Mrs McCrae'''}}{{Anchor|Mrs McCrae}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Reylene Pearce]]<ref name=\"Nannies\">{{cite episode|title=Episode 728|series=Neighbours |serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Colin Budds; Writer: Ray Harding|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=19 May 1988}}</ref>}}\n| Mrs McCrae applies for the position of nanny to [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]]'s son, [[Jamie Clarke (Neighbours)|Jamie]], but is unsuccessful due to her stern demeanour. She later applies at Lassiter's for the position of housekeeper and remarks that [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] is a little young to be in charge of the complex.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|19\u201320 May}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Carol Barker'''}}{{Anchor|Carol Barker}}\n| {{nowrap|Louise Siversen<ref name=\"Nannies\"/>}}\n| Carol answers [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]]'s advert for a nanny to his son [[Jamie Clarke (Neighbours)|Jamie]]. Carol is a nurse but wants the freedom that the lifestyle of a nanny offers and Des agrees to hire her on the spot. When Jamie cries loudly for his lunch, Carol lets him cry. Des' neighbour [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]] is concerned but Carol reassures her everything is fine and refuses to let her see Jamie. When Des arrives home, he notices Jamie is cranky and Gail tells him about Carol. The following day, the same thing happens and Des feeds Jamie himself. Carol then tells Des that Jamie will end up spoiled. Des then promptly tells Carol, to leave which she does.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|24 May 1988,<br>1 November 1993,<br>7 March 1994}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Prue Watkins'''}}{{Anchor|Prue Watkins}}\n| {{nowrap|Lindsay Worthington<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 732|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Kendal Flanagan; Writer: [[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=24 May 1988}}</ref>}}<br />{{nowrap|Jacyl Shaw<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 2036|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Alan Coleman; Directors: Philip East and Grant Fenn; Writer: John Upton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=1 November 1993}}</ref>}}<br />{{nowrap|Olivia Davis<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 2101|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Alan Coleman; Director: Tony Osicka; Writer: Helen MacWhirter|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=7 March 1994}}</ref>}}\n| A receptionist at Lassiter's. Her colleague [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]] and [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] set her up on a date with [[David Bishop (Neighbours)|David Bishop]]. David asks Prue out on a second date but she rejects him. Prue reappears sparingly over the next few years.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|2\u201330 June}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Steve Fisher'''}}{{Anchor|Steve Fisher}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Michael Pope (producer)|Michael Pope]] <ref>[[#refkercher|Kercher 1989]], p.53.</ref>}}\n| [[Charlene Robinson]]'s driving instructor, they become friendly while Charlene is in Brisbane visiting her grandparents [[Dan Ramsay|Dan]] and [[Edna Ramsay]]. Charlene's husband [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott]] is jealous, but she reassures him nothing is going on. When Charlene passes her test, she and Steve share a kiss and Charlene is wracked with guilt and confesses to Scott. Charlene's brother [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] warns Steve to keep away, but he is undeterred. Steve then offers Charlene a choice, him or Scott and she chooses her husband. Steve then returns to Brisbane. \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|17 June\u20138 July}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Ian Chadwick'''}}{{Anchor|Ian Chadwick}}\n| {{nowrap|Robin Bowering<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1989-10-06#at-13.30|title=BBC London 6 October 1989 13:30|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| [[Gail Robinson (Neighbours)|Gail Robinson]]'s biological father. He reappears when Gail tracks him down and they begin to build up a relationship but Gail's adoptive father, [[Rob Lewis (Neighbours)|Rob Lewis]] is jealous and tries to sabotage Ian's attempts to get to closer to Gail. The final straw comes when Rob breaks a present Ian buys for Gail and her husband [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul]]'s first wedding anniversary and refuses to apologize. Gail is angry at first but Rob calms down and apologizes and gives Ian his blessing to remain in contact with Gail.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|17\u201328 June}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Rachel Frazer'''}}{{Anchor|Rachel Frazer}}\n| {{nowrap|Pamela Hawkesford<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1989-09-25#at-13.30|title=BBC London 25 September 1989 13:30|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| A basketball player who meets [[Scott Robinson (Neighbours)|Scott Robinson]], [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] and [[Pete Baxter (Neighbours)|Pete Baxter]] when they visit the [[Australian Institute of Sport]]  in [[Canberra]] when Pete is awarded a place there and is assigned Rachel as a mentor. There is an attraction between Mike and Rachel and they begin dating, but Rachel makes it clear basketball is priority. When Pete injures himself and has to see a doctor, he blames Scott but Rachel admits she was the one who informed Pete's trainers about Pete's injury. When the guys leave the institute to return to Erinsborough, Pete thanks Rachel for her all her help. Rachel then tells Mike he needs to get over his ex-girlfriend [[Jane Harris (Neighbours)|Jane Harris]]. Several weeks later, When Pete disappears from the institute and turns up in Erinsborough and says he could no longer handle it there, Rachel calls Mike to tell him the truth behind Pete's disappearance from the institute, which forces Pete to come clean and admit that he has exacerbated his injury.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| {{nowrap|21\u201322 June}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Carl Banks'''}}{{Anchor|Carl Banks}}\n| {{nowrap|Don Bridges<ref>{{cite web|url=https://donbridges.com/cv/television/|title= Don Bridges CV - Television|publisher=donbridges.com|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}} \n| A kitchen hand at Lassiter's. [[Nell Mangel]] is suspicious of him, despite Carl being highly praised by management. Nell tells [[Paul Robinson (Neighbours)|Paul Robinson]] that Carl has been stealing from the kitchen. Carl protests his innocence but when Paul opens up a bag, he finds various items of food from the kitchen and Carl is subsequently arrested and charged. However, Carl is released due to lack of a criminal record. He then forces his way into Number 32, blaming Nell for costing him his job and threatens to harm her and make it look like an accident. [[Bronwyn Davies]] arrives home and witnesses the situation and grabs an umbrella and is able to chase Carl out of the house.\n|-\n| {{nowrap|'''Bob Hughes'''}}{{Anchor|Bob Hughes}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Jim Daly (actor)|Jim Daly]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bgmagency.com.au/uploaded/cv/DALY%20Jim.pdf|title=Jim Daly|publisher=BGM Agency|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| Bob is a regular customer at the Waterhole pub who makes sarcastic comments about the new uniforms the bar staff have been told to wear. When Bob begins making drunken lecherous comments to [[Madge Bishop]], her son, [[Henry Ramsay (Neighbours)|Henry Ramsay]] pushes Bob and he falls over. Bob then sues for damages. Madge tries to talk him out of it but he is adamant. However, When he gets his medical report back, Bob calls off the suit.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|19 August}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Gary Ling'''}}{{Anchor|Gary Ling}}\n| {{nowrap|Lee Chong}}\n| A Year 8 classmate of [[Todd Landers]]. He enters an ice-cream eating contest at the coffee shop along with Todd and several others, but the event quickly turns into a food fight, resulting in [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] disqualifying all contestants.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|26 August 1988 \u2013 31 January 1989}} \n| {{nowrap|'''Penelope Porter'''}}{{Anchor|Penelope Porter}}\n| {{nowrap|Nikki Wendt}}\n| A new assistant manager at the Erinsborough branch of the Pacific Bank. She and colleague [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des Clarke]] become very friendly and there is an attraction, but Des is reluctant to take things further as his wife [[Daphne Clarke|Daphne]] has recently died. Dejected, Penny then transfers back to head office. She reappears when Des suffers from an allergy and replaces him at the bank. She admits she has been seeing their boss Gordon Hemmings for a while but after spending the evening with Des, they share a kiss. Des plans to propose after it seems like Penny and Gordon will break up but Penny announces she and Gordon are leaving for Europe, breaking Des' heart.\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|29 August}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Margaret Brownley'''}}{{Anchor|Margaret Brownley}}\n| {{nowrap|Maggie Seren<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 801|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Max Varnel; Writer: Ian Coughlan|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=29 August 1988}}</ref>}}\n| A patient of [[Beverly Marshall]], who suffers an Asthma attack one day in the coffee shop. Beverly acts quickly but Margaret dies en route to hospital. Worse news is to come when the cause of Margaret's death is an overdose as a result of Beverly administering a shot when Margaret had been taking medication orally.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2\u20135 September\n| {{nowrap|'''Brad Fuller'''}}{{Anchor|Brad Fuller}}\n| {{nowrap|Scott Snibson<ref name=\"Unimates\">{{cite episode|title=Episode 805|series=Neighbours |serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Max Varnel; Writer: Lois Booton|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=2 September 1988}}</ref>}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| University friends of [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]], who arrive for a study session with Mike at Number 28. While Brad gets along with Mike's girlfriend, [[Bronwyn Davies]], who also works as a live-in nanny, Jackie clashes with Bronwyn by putting down her occupation and making rude comments when she learns Bronwyn did not receive her HSC after dropping out of school to help family on the farm after her mother's death. Several weeks later, at a fete for the local church, Jackie continues putting Bronwyn down and receives a cream pie in the face for her trouble. After Bronwyn refuses to apologize, Jackie storms off.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2 September\u20135 October\n| {{nowrap|'''Jackie Vidor'''}}{{Anchor|Jackie Vidor}}\n| {{nowrap|Shona Ford<ref name=\"Unimates\"/>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|9 September 1988 \u2013 6 June 1989}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Bruce Zadro'''}}{{Anchor|Bruce Zadro}}\n| {{nowrap|Myles Collins<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 810|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Richard Sarrell; Writer: C.V. Schofield|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=9 September 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Nick Page]]'s nemesis at Erinsborough High. He causes trouble at the school dance by making unwanted advances towards Nick's date [[Sharon Davies]] and he and Nick get into a fight, resulting in Nick receiving a black eye ahead of his court date for graffiti. Zadro later frames Nick for tagging principal [[Kenneth Muir (Neighbours)|Kenneth Muir]]'s car, which sees him expelled as a result. Sharon, eager to avenge Nick, concocts a scheme to get Zadro to reveal himself as the truth culprit by pretending to flirt with him and tricks him into confessing over the school tannoy and Nick is reinstated while Zadro is expelled. Nick and Zadro later enter a skateboarding competition where the stipulation is if Zadro wins, he gets a date with Sharon. However, Nick injures himself during practice and [[Matt Robinson (Neighbours)|Matt Williams]] agrees to compete in his place and beats Zadro.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|12 September}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Andrew Brownley'''}}{{Anchor|Andrew Brownley}}\n| {{nowrap|Ian Murton<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bgmagency.com.au/uploaded/cv/MURTON%20Iain.pdf|title=Ian Murton CV|publisher=BGM Agency|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n| [[#Margaret Brownley|Margaret Brownley]]'s son. Following Margaret's death, Andrew blames [[Beverly Marshall]], who attended to Margaret and threatens to sue for Malpractice. Beverly's husband, [[Jim Robinson (Neighbours)|Jim Robinson]] tries to reason with him but Andrew is unrepentant and takes the suit to court. However, Beverly is found not to be at fault.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|20 September 1988 \u2013 17 February 1989}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Vanessa Bailey'''}}{{Anchor|Vanessa Bailey}}\n| {{nowrap|Gretchen Zoland<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 817|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Tony Osicka; Writer: Ray Harding|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=20 September 1988}}</ref>}}\n| A classmate of [[Sharon Davies]] and [[Nick Page]]. She and her friend Pam Muir offer Sharon a cigarette while she is working at the Coffee Shop. Sharon is reluctant but Vanessa and Pam begin taunting her. Sharon takes a puff and dislikes it then throws the cigarette away into a bin, which causes a huge fire. Several months later, Vanessa suggests Nick asks [[#Kenneth Muir|Mr Muir]] if he can paint a mural on a blank wall at the school. However, Nick's plans are cut short when Muir's car is graffitied and he is blamed for it.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|12 October\u20134 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Jessie Ross'''}}{{Anchor|Jessie Ross}}\n| {{nowrap|[[Michelle Kearley]]<ref name=\"Rosses\">{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-02-05#at-13.30|title=Neighbours BBC One London 13:30 5 February 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}} \n| A Year 10 student, who attends a party thrown by classmate [[Sharon Davies]]. She is attracted to [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] who is due to start at his alma mater [[Erinsborough High]] as their teacher. When Jessie arrives with a bruised face to a study session, it causes concern. Mike discovers Jessie's mother [[#Adele Ross|Adele]] is the one hitting her after suspecting her father [[#Ted Ross|Ted]]. When Mike and Jessie have a tutoring session one day after school, their emotions get the best of them and they share a kiss only to be caught by principal  [[Kenneth Muir (Neighbours)|Kenneth Muir]], who angrily suspends Mike. Jessie is then sent to live with her grandparents and tells Mike she loves him before leaving.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|21 October\u20134 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Ted Ross'''}}{{Anchor|Ted Ross}}\n| {{nowrap|Doug Bennett<ref name=\"Rosses\"/>}} \n| The father of [[#Jessie Ross|Jessie Ross]]. Jessie's teacher [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] suspects Ted of beating her when she begins attending school bruised and becomes cagey about the subject of her parents. Mike arrives at the house one day to find that Ted is not the culprit but his wife [[#Adele Ross|Adele]]. After a talk, Mike gives the Rosses a number to call to get some professional help and Ted is grateful. However, after Mike is caught in a compromising position with Jessie, he is livid and makes a threat that Mike will never teach in any other school.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|25\u201326 October}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Adele Ross'''}}{{Anchor|Adele Ross}}\n| {{nowrap|Marian Sinclair<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-02-05|title=Neighbours BBC One London 13:30 2 February 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>}}  \n| The mother of [[#Jessie Ross|Jessie Ross]]. Jessie's teacher, [[Mike Young (Neighbours)|Mike Young]] arrives at their house and learns that Adele is responsible for Jessie's bruises after overhearing shouting. Mike confronts Adele and she threatens to call police if he does not leave but he calls her bluff by saying the police may be interested in learning the full extent of Jessie's bruises. Adele's husband, [[#Ted Ross|Ted]] arrives home and they discuss matters with Mike and after a long discussion, Mike puts the Rosses in touch with a counsellor.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|7\u201317 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Leanne Sterling'''}}{{Anchor|Leanne Sterling}}\n| {{nowrap|[[May Lloyd]]<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 851|series=Neighbours|serieslink=Neighbours|credits=Executive producer: Don Battye; Director: Julian McSwiney; Writer: Ray Kolle|network=[[Network Ten]]|airdate=7 November 1988}}</ref>}}\n| [[Malcolm Clarke (Neighbours)|Malcolm Clarke]]'s girlfriend. There is a big age difference between the two and Malcolm is eager to impress Leanne so he lies that he is wealthy and his son [[Des Clarke (Neighbours)|Des]]' house belongs to him and Des lives there. Malcolm introduces Leanne to his family and leaves her to get acquainted with Des. She begins flirting with Des and making unwanted advances towards him, making him uncomfortable. When she tries to kiss Des and he rejects her, Malcolm walks in and witnesses this and Leanne invents a story that Des made a pass at her after slapping him. Malcolm initially believes Leanne, but Des snaps and urges them to be honest with each other. Leanne then leaves.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|10 November 1988 \u2013 20 February 1990}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Noeline Mangel'''}}{{Anchor|Noeline Mangel}}\n| {{nowrap|Lindy McConchie}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-04-09#at-13.30|title=Schedules: BBC One 9 April 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Joe Mangel]]'s ex-wife. She brings their son [[Toby Mangel|Toby]] to live with Joe while she marries her new partner, Ted Vickers. Noeline returns to collect Toby along with Ted but Toby is reluctant to go as Ted has a temper. When Ted hits Toby for making a mess during dinner, Joe threatens Ted and throws both him and Noeline out. In desperation, Noeline turns to [[#Edith Chubb|Edith Chubb]], who has a grudge against Joe, for help. While Joe is out, Noeline snatches Toby back and returns home only to find Ted does not want Toby living with them and goes to hit her but Joe overpowers him and rescues Toby and Noeline. Toby tries to reunite Joe and Noeline but fails, much to his disappointment. Noeline later receives a job in Darwin and wants Toby to join her, and after some reluctance and some arguing between Joe and Noeline, Toby agrees to live with Noeline and they leave. However, two months later, Noeline is killed in a road accident and Toby returns to Joe.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| {{nowrap|30 November}}\n| {{nowrap|'''Eva Lindstrom'''}}{{Anchor|Eva Lindstrom}}\n| {{nowrap|Lana Darby}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbcone/london/1990-03-12|title=Schedules: BBC One 12 March 1990|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n| A Scandinavian masseuse who tends to [[Harold Bishop]] when he suffers from a back spasm. She visits him at his home and administers treatment, which is successful.\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last=Hopwood|first=Clive|title=The Official Neighbours Annual 1990|year=1989|publisher=World International|isbn=978-0-7235-6859-9|ref=refhopwood}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wallis|first1=Neil|last2=Hogan|first2=Dave|title=The Neighbours Factfile|year=1989|publisher=[[Angus & Robertson]]|isbn=978-0-207-16382-1|ref=refwallis}}\n* {{cite book|title=Neighbours: The First 10 Years|last=Monroe|first=Josephine|year=1996|publisher=[[Penguin Group]]|isbn=978-0-7181-4212-4|ref=refmonroe|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/neighboursfirst10000monr}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Neighbours Programme Guide|last=Monroe|first=Josephine|year=1994|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|isbn=978-0-86369-831-6|ref=refmonroe2}}\